            {
              "id": "0127f894-9782-347c-89ab-77bc2bc2857f",
              "name": "User Controlled Data Can Lead To XSS Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn JavaScript, the `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, and `document.write` methods are commonly used to manipulate the HTML content of an element. However, if the data being inserted is controlled by the user and not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS vulnerabilities.\n\nIn the given code snippet, `newdiv.innerHTML = html;`, the `html` variable is directly assigned to `innerHTML` without any sanitization or encoding. If `html` contains malicious script, it will be executed when the HTML is rendered by the browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use the textContent property instead of innerHTML to insert text from users.\n- Use element.setAttribute() instead of direct assignment to properties.\n- Use a safe, context-specific encoding library to encode user-supplied input.\n- Validate user input on the server-side as well as on the client-side.\n- Use Content Security Policy (CSP) to mitigate the impact of any potential XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `innerHTML`, use `textContent`:\n\n```javascript\nnewdiv.textContent = html;\n```\n\nThis will treat the input as text and not as HTML code, preventing any scripts from being executed.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
