            {
              "id": "01d260f3-0d61-3b8b-9f3a-bfc34d8ed917",
              "name": "Promise Without Catch Handler",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unhandled Promise Rejection Vulnerability\" in JavaScript occurs when a promise is rejected, but this rejection is not caught or handled. This can lead to unexpected application behavior and potential security vulnerabilities. In the context of the provided code, if the AJAX request fails for any reason (e.g., server error, network issues), the promise returned by `$.ajax` will be rejected. However, there's no `.catch` or `.fail` handler to handle this rejection, leading to an Unhandled Promise Rejection.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always handle promise rejections by adding a `.catch` or `.fail` handler to your promises. This handler can take appropriate action when the promise is rejected, such as logging the error or notifying the user.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere's how you can fix the provided code:\n\n```javascript\n$.ajax({\n    type: 'POST',\n    url: 'CrossSiteScriptingStored/stored-xss',\n    data: JSON.stringify({text: commentInput}),\n    contentType: \"application/json\",\n    dataType: 'json'\n}).then(\n    function () {\n        getChallenges();\n        $(\"#commentInput\").val('');\n    }\n).catch(\n    function (error) {\n        console.error('An error occurred:', error);\n        // Handle the error appropriately here\n    }\n);\n```\n\nIn this fixed code, a `.catch` handler is added to handle any promise rejections.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- jQuery: For the `$` function, AJAX functionality, and promise methods.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unhandled Promise Rejection](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Nodejs_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html#unhandled-promise-rejections)\n- [CWE-754: Improper Check for Unusual or Exceptional Conditions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/754.html)"
              },
