              "id": "07d4b70a-b5ca-3a50-ac36-931b59d99b98",
              "name": "User Controlled Data Can Lead To XSS Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when data enters a program from an untrusted source and is used to generate dynamic HTML content. The jQuery `.html(...)` function is a common source of XSS vulnerabilities because it interprets the argument as HTML. If this argument is user-controlled data, an attacker can inject malicious scripts that will be executed in the context of the victim's browser.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `votes[i]` is directly passed to the `.html(...)` function, which can lead to an XSS vulnerability if `votes[i]` contains user-controlled data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `.html(...)` function with user-controlled data. Instead, use text-based methods like `.text(...)` which do not interpret the input as HTML. If you need to use HTML content, make sure to properly sanitize the user-controlled data before using it.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the vulnerable line with the following:\n\n```javascript\n$(\"#nrOfVotes\" + i).text(votes[i]);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the jQuery library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
