              "id": "0d436821-38a6-3379-ae2a-19563a7abb3f",
              "name": "JWT Handling Accepts Alg=None Header Value",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe JWT vulnerability: Acceptance of `alg=none` header value is a security flaw in Java programming language where an attacker can bypass the signature verification step in the JWT authentication process. This is possible when the JWT library accepts `alg=none` in the JWT header, which indicates that the token is not signed and therefore should not be verified. An attacker can exploit this vulnerability by sending a JWT with `alg=none` and a payload of their choice, which the server will accept as a valid token.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should ensure that your JWT library does not accept `alg=none` in the JWT header. You should also ensure that your JWT library verifies the signature of the JWT before accepting it as valid. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nYou can fix this vulnerability by adding a check to ensure that the `alg` value in the JWT header is not `none`. Here is an example of how you can do this:\n\n```java\nString alg = jwt.getHeader().get(\"alg\");\nif (\"none\".equals(alg)) {\n    throw new SecurityException(\"Invalid alg value: \" + alg);\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `javax.security.auth.message.AuthException`\n- `io.jsonwebtoken.Jwts`\n- `io.jsonwebtoken.Claims`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP JWT Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/JSON_Web_Token_Cheat_Sheet_for_Java.html)\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: A6-Security Misconfiguration](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A6_2017-Security_Misconfiguration)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-347: Improper Verification of Cryptographic Signature](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/347.html)"
              },
