            {
              "id": "16fd6e42-60bd-3019-bedd-cf94f4ddb207",
              "name": "User Controlled Data In HTML String May Result In XSS",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the application is taking user-controlled data (`result`) and directly appending it to a data URL which is then set as the source of an image element. If an attacker can control the `result` variable, they could potentially inject malicious scripts, leading to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should:\n\n1. **Validate Input**: Ensure that the user-controlled data is what you expect. For example, if you're expecting an image in base64 format, ensure that the input matches this format.\n\n2. **Encode Output**: Ensure that the output is encoded so that any potentially harmful characters are neutralized.\n\n3. **Use Appropriate Response Headers**: To prevent any kind of XSS via HTTP response headers, always use the `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff` header.\n\n4. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Implementing CSP would add an extra layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including XSS and data injection attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```javascript\nlet base64Format = /^data:image\\/png;base64,([A-Za-z0-9+/]{4})*([A-Za-z0-9+/]{2}==|[A-Za-z0-9+/]{3}=)?$/;\n\nif(base64Format.test(\"data:image/png;base64,\" + result)) {\n    document.getElementById(\"previewFix\").src = \"data:image/png;base64,\" + result;\n} else {\n    console.error(\"Invalid base64 input\");\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we're using a regular expression to validate that the `result` variable is a valid base64 image before setting it as the source of the image element.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
