            {
              "id": "1f83d7a9-95cc-3ed9-a9e1-bf103938cc2f",
              "name": "Spring Endpoint",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Spring Endpoint Vulnerability in Java is a type of security vulnerability that occurs when an application built with the Spring Framework exposes sensitive information or functionality through its endpoints. This can lead to unauthorized access or data leakage. In the provided code, the vulnerability lies in the handling of JSON and XML content types. If an attacker can manipulate the content type and inject malicious content, it can lead to an XML External Entity (XXE) attack.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to:\n\n1. Validate all inputs: Ensure that all incoming data is validated before processing. This includes checking for the correct data type, length, format, and range.\n\n2. Use secure configuration: Ensure that the application is configured securely, and that sensitive information is not exposed through endpoints.\n\n3. Implement proper error handling: Do not reveal sensitive information in error messages. \n\n4. Update libraries: Ensure that all libraries used by the application are up-to-date and do not contain known vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe code should be updated to properly handle and sanitize the input data. Here is a recommended fix:\n\n```java\nif (APPLICATION_JSON_VALUE.equals(contentType)) {\n  comments.parseJson(commentStr).ifPresent(c -> comments.addComment(c, true));\n  attackResult = failed(this).feedback(\"xxe.content.type.feedback.json\").build();\n}\n\nif (null != contentType && contentType.contains(MediaType.APPLICATION_XML_VALUE)) {\n  String error = \"\";\n  try {\n    Comment comment = comments.parseXml(Sanitizer.sanitize(commentStr));\n    comments.addComment(comment, false);\n    if (checkSolution(comment)) {\n      attackResult = success(this).build();\n    }\n  } catch (Exception e) {\n    error = ExceptionUtils.getStackTrace(e);\n    attackResult = failed(this).feedback(\"xxe.content.type.feedback.xml\").output(error).build();\n  }\n}\n\nreturn attackResult;\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Spring Framework\n- Apache Commons Lang (for `ExceptionUtils`)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XXE Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/XML_External_Entity_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-611: Improper Restriction of XML External Entity Reference ('XXE')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/611.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-611",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/611.html"
                  }
                ],
