            {
              "id": "1fa7b25c-fe4c-3fc8-b0f7-bf3a558b5ba7",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability In jQuery HTML Manipulation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Dynamic Input HTML Manipulation in jQuery: Sanitization and Plain Text Content Vulnerability\" is a common security vulnerability in JavaScript programming language. It occurs when an application includes user-controllable data in a jQuery `.html()` call which can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. This happens because the `.html()` method in jQuery sets the HTML content of an element, but it does not sanitize the input, making it possible to inject malicious scripts.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use the `.text()` method instead of `.html()`. The `.text()` method automatically escapes HTML tags and thus prevents the execution of any injected scripts. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the vulnerable line of code with the following:\n\n```javascript\n$(\"#voteResultMsg\").text(result[\"message\"]);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library to execute properly:\n\n- jQuery\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "204e7930-4551-34f1-b0f5-a3f33485d5ad",
              "name": "Weak Random Number Generator Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Insecure Use of Non-Cryptographically Strong RNGs in Password or Token Generation\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a developer uses a non-cryptographically strong Random Number Generator (RNG) to generate a password, token, or other security-sensitive values. In Java, the `java.util.Random` class is not suitable for generating such values because it's predictable and can be easily brute-forced.\n\nIn the provided code, a PIN code is generated using `java.util.Random`. This is insecure because an attacker could predict the PIN code, leading to unauthorized access.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, use a cryptographically strong RNG. In Java, you can use `java.security.SecureRandom` instead of `java.util.Random`. `SecureRandom` generates random numbers in a way that is safe for cryptographic use.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```java\nimport java.security.SecureRandom;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static final int PINCODE;\n    \n    static {\n        SecureRandom random = new SecureRandom();\n        PINCODE = random.nextInt(10000);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe fixed code requires no additional library dependencies. It uses the `java.security.SecureRandom` class, which is part of the Java standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Randomness](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Randomness)\n- [CWE-338: Use of Cryptographically Weak Pseudo-Random Number Generator (PRNG)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/338.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-338",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/338.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-338"
                ]
              }
