            {
              "id": "223a6a8e-f236-337a-a69a-9403bad251d2",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability In jQuery HTML Manipulation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Dynamic Input HTML Manipulation in jQuery: Sanitization and Plain Text Content Vulnerability\" is a security vulnerability in JavaScript programming language that occurs when user input is directly embedded into the HTML document without proper sanitization or validation. This can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks, where an attacker can inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, `$(field).append(comment);`, the `comment` variable is directly appended to the `field` element without any sanitization. If the `comment` variable contains malicious scripts, it can lead to XSS attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and validate user inputs before embedding them into the HTML document. This can be done by using the `text()` method in jQuery, which automatically escapes any HTML tags in the input.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```javascript\n$(field).append($('<div>').text(comment));\n```\n\nIn this code, the `comment` variable is first passed to the `text()` method, which escapes any HTML tags in the input. The result is then appended to the `field` element.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library to execute properly:\n\n- jQuery\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2280ba27-98b4-3e8b-b3cd-e5655caafaf3",
              "name": "XML Parsing Vulnerable To XXE",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nXML External Entity (XXE) vulnerability in XML parsing is a type of security vulnerability that occurs when an application processing XML input allows the inclusion of external entities. The XMLStreamReader in Java is susceptible to this vulnerability if not properly configured. An attacker can exploit this vulnerability to read local files on the server, interact with any back-end or external systems that the application can access, or perform a Denial-of-Service attack.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XXE vulnerabilities, it's recommended to disable Document Type Definitions (DTDs) in your XML parser configuration. This can be done by setting the `IS_SUPPORTING_EXTERNAL_ENTITIES` and `SUPPORT_DTD` features to `false`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that shows how to disable DTDs in XMLStreamReader:\n\n```java\nimport javax.xml.stream.XMLInputFactory;\nimport javax.xml.stream.XMLStreamReader;\nimport java.io.StringReader;\n\nXMLInputFactory xif = XMLInputFactory.newFactory();\nxif.setProperty(XMLInputFactory.SUPPORT_DTD, false); // This disables DTDs entirely for that factory\nxif.setProperty(XMLInputFactory.IS_SUPPORTING_EXTERNAL_ENTITIES, false); // disable external entities\n\nString xml = \"<foo>bar</foo>\";\nXMLStreamReader xsr = xif.createXMLStreamReader(new StringReader(xml));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- `javax.xml.stream` which is a part of Java SE (Standard Edition).\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XXE Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/XML_External_Entity_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-611: Improper Restriction of XML External Entity Reference ('XXE')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/611.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-611",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/611.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-611"
                ]
              }
