            {
              "id": "2a7b4086-a0e0-3ee0-9ee5-38e88829589b",
              "name": "User Controlled Data Can Lead To XSS Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn JavaScript, methods like `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `document.write` can introduce XSS vulnerabilities if they are used to insert user-controlled data into the DOM. In the provided code example, the `innerHTML` property is used to insert the HTML content of an element with a user-controlled ID into another element. If an attacker can control the ID of the element, they can inject arbitrary HTML content, including malicious scripts, into the page.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use text content instead of HTML when inserting user-controlled data into the DOM. This can be done using the `textContent` property instead of `innerHTML`.\n- If you need to insert HTML content, sanitize it first to remove any potentially harmful scripts. This can be done using a library like DOMPurify.\n- Use Content Security Policy (CSP) to restrict the sources from which scripts can be loaded. This can prevent the execution of injected scripts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code example:\n\n```javascript\ndocument.getElementById(\"employeeRecord\").textContent = document.getElementById(newEmployeeID).textContent;\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [DOM Based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
