            {
              "id": "2b5934ba-75d4-35d7-bf2f-9f753db8c6f4",
              "name": "Hardcoded Anti-CSRF Token Comparison",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAnti-CSRF Token Hardcoding Vulnerability refers to a security flaw where the CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery) token, used to prevent CSRF attacks, is hardcoded into the application. This makes the application vulnerable to CSRF attacks as the token can be easily discovered and exploited by attackers. In the provided Java code, the CSRF token (`weakAntiCSRF`) is being compared with the request token (`validateReq`). If they are not equal, the request is considered invalid.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid hardcoding CSRF tokens. Instead, generate a new token for each session or request. Store this token securely on the server side and include it as a hidden field in the form on the client side. When a form is submitted, compare the submitted token with the one stored on the server side. If they match, the request is valid; if not, reject the request.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```java\n// Generate a new CSRF token for each session\nString csrfToken = generateNewToken();\n\n// Store the token in the session\nrequest.getSession().setAttribute(\"csrfToken\", csrfToken);\n\n// In the form handling method\nString requestToken = request.getParameter(\"csrfToken\");\nString sessionToken = (String) request.getSession().getAttribute(\"csrfToken\");\n\nif (sessionToken == null || !sessionToken.equals(requestToken)) {\n    return failed(this).feedback(\"csrf-you-forgot-something\").build();\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not specify any library dependencies. However, it is likely to require the following:\n\n- `javax.servlet-api` for handling HTTP requests and responses.\n- A library for generating CSRF tokens, such as `owasp-java-encoder`.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
