              "id": "32ac19fe-18fc-39d2-b92b-384eff64b23a",
              "name": "Promise Without Catch Handler",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unhandled Promise Rejection Vulnerability\" in JavaScript occurs when a Promise is rejected, but this rejection is not caught or handled. This can lead to unexpected application behavior, including crashes, and can potentially expose sensitive information in error messages. \n\nIn the provided code, the Promise returned by the `$.ajax` call is not handling any potential rejections. If the POST request fails for any reason (e.g., server error, network issues), the Promise will be rejected and this rejection will not be caught, leading to an Unhandled Promise Rejection.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always handle Promise rejections. This can be done by adding a `.catch` block to the Promise chain. The `.catch` block will be executed if the Promise is rejected, allowing you to handle the error appropriately.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```javascript\n$.ajax({\n    type: 'POST',\n    url: 'JWT/votings/' + title\n}).then(\n    function () {\n        getVotings();\n    }\n).catch(\n    function (error) {\n        console.error('An error occurred:', error);\n        // Handle the error appropriately here\n    }\n);\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, a `.catch` block has been added to the Promise chain. If the Promise is rejected, the function provided to `.catch` will be executed, logging the error and allowing for appropriate error handling.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- jQuery: The `$` function and `.ajax` method are part of jQuery.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Unhandled Promise Rejection](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Nodejs_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html#unhandled-promise-rejections)\n- [CWE-754: Improper Check for Unusual or Exceptional Conditions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/754.html)"
              },
