            {
              "id": "37327ea5-a36c-3420-8f4e-4a644201ce8f",
              "name": "Potential JDBC Injection",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "\nThe input values included in SQL queries need to be passed in safely. Bind variables in prepared statements can be used to easily mitigate the risk of SQL injection. Alternatively to prepare statements, each parameter can be escaped manually.\n\n**Solution (Prepared Statements):**\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM User WHERE id = ?\";\nPreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npreparedStatement.setString(1, inputId);\nResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery();\n```\n\n**Solution (Encoding):**\n\n```java\nimport org.owasp.esapi.Encoder;\ncreateQuery(\"select * from User where id = '\" + Encoder.encodeForSQL(inputId) + \"'\");\n```\n\n## In Context Remediation\n```\nVulnerable Query: \"SELECT * FROM employees WHERE last_name = '\" + name + \"' AND auth_tan = '\" + auth_tan + \"'\"\nRemediated Query: ## Description\n\nThis code builds a SQL query by concatenating untrusted input directly into the statement text. In Java JDBC code, this allows an attacker to change the meaning of the query by supplying crafted values for name or auth_tan, which can expose records that should not be returned.\n\nThe correct fix is to use a PreparedStatement with bind parameters. Parameterized queries keep data separate from SQL syntax, so user input is treated as a value rather than executable SQL. This is the standard and reliable mitigation for SQL injection in Java applications.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse PreparedStatement for every query that includes external input, including SELECT, UPDATE, INSERT, and DELETE statements. Never assemble SQL by concatenating request parameters, form fields, headers, cookies, or other untrusted values into the query string.\n\nIf parts of a query cannot be parameterized, such as column names or sort direction, map user input to a fixed allowlist of expected values before building the SQL. Run the database account with the minimum privileges required, and avoid exposing sensitive error details to callers.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~java\nString sql = \"SELECT * FROM employees WHERE last_name = ? AND auth_tan = ?\";\n\ntry (PreparedStatement pstmt = connection.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n    pstmt.setString(1, name);\n    pstmt.setString(2, auth_tan);\n\n    try (ResultSet rs = pstmt.executeQuery()) {\n        while (rs.next()) {\n            // process result set\n        }\n    }\n}\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~java\nimport java.sql.PreparedStatement;\nimport java.sql.ResultSet;\nimport java.sql.SQLException;\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Oracle JDBC Tutorial: Using Prepared Statements](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/jdbc/basics/prepared.html)\n\n```\n#### Remediation\n```xml\n<!-- pom.xml -->\n<dependencies>\n  <!-- JDBC driver -->\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    <version>2.2.224</version>\n  </dependency>\n</dependencies>\n```\n\n```java\n// SqlInjectionPreventionDemo.java\nimport java.sql.*;\n\npublic class SqlInjectionPreventionDemo {\n  public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n    String url = \"jdbc:h2:mem:test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1\";\n\n    try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url)) {\n      setup(con);\n\n      String name = \"Smith\";\n      String authTan = \"12345\";\n\n      // Vulnerable:\n      String unsafe = \"SELECT * FROM employees WHERE last_name = '\" + name\n          + \"' AND auth_tan = '\" + authTan + \"'\";\n      System.out.println(\"Unsafe SQL: \" + unsafe);\n\n      // Attack input:\n      String evilName = \"' OR '1'='1\";\n      String evilTan = \"' OR '1'='1\";\n\n      System.out.println(\"Unsafe result count: \" + unsafeQuery(con, evilName, evilTan));\n      System.out.println(\"Safe result count:   \" + safeQuery(con, evilName, evilTan));\n    }\n  }\n\n  static void setup(Connection con) throws SQLException {\n    try (Statement st = con.createStatement()) {\n      st.execute(\"CREATE TABLE employees (id INT, last_name VARCHAR(100), auth_tan VARCHAR(100))\");\n      st.execute(\"INSERT INTO employees VALUES (1, 'Smith', '12345')\");\n      st.execute(\"INSERT INTO employees VALUES (2, 'Jones', '99999')\");\n    }\n  }\n\n  static int unsafeQuery(Connection con, String name, String authTan) throws SQLException {\n    String sql = \"SELECT * FROM employees WHERE last_name = '\" + name\n        + \"' AND auth_tan = '\" + authTan + \"'\";\n    try (Statement st = con.createStatement(); ResultSet rs = st.executeQuery(sql)) {\n      return count(rs);\n    }\n  }\n\n  static int safeQuery(Connection con, String name, String authTan) throws SQLException {\n    String sql = \"SELECT * FROM employees WHERE last_name = ? AND auth_tan = ?\";\n    try (PreparedStatement ps = con.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n      ps.setString(1, name);\n      ps.setString(2, authTan);\n      try (ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) {\n        return count(rs);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  static int count(ResultSet rs) throws SQLException {\n    int n = 0;\n    while (rs.next()) n++;\n    return n;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nRun:\n```bash\njavac SqlInjectionPreventionDemo.java\njava -cp .:h2-2.2.224.jar SqlInjectionPreventionDemo\n```\n\nWhy safe: `PreparedStatement` sends SQL and data separately, so attacker input is treated as a literal string, not executable SQL.\n\nAlternative JDBC drivers:\n- PostgreSQL: `org.postgresql:postgresql`\n- MySQL: `com.mysql:mysql-connector-j`\n- MariaDB: `org.mariadb.jdbc:mariadb-java-client`\n- SQLite: `org.xerial:sqlite-jdbc`\n- Microsoft SQL Server: `com.microsoft.sqlserver:mssql-jdbc`\n\n___\n\n\n**References (SQL injection)**\n\n- [CAPEC-66: SQL Injection](https://capec.mitre.org/data/definitions/66.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [OWASP: Top 10 A03_2021-Injection](https://owasp.org/Top10/A03_2021-Injection/)\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet)\n- [OWASP: Query Parameterization Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Query_Parameterization_Cheat_Sheet)\n\n\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "3.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
