              "id": "386ff6ff-3c23-3f58-9725-09f796909570",
              "name": "Potential JDBC Injection",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "\nThe input values included in SQL queries need to be passed in safely. Bind variables in prepared statements can be used to easily mitigate the risk of SQL injection. Alternatively to prepare statements, each parameter can be escaped manually.\n\n**Solution (Prepared Statements):**\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM User WHERE id = ?\";\nPreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npreparedStatement.setString(1, inputId);\nResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery();\n```\n\n**Solution (Encoding):**\n\n```java\nimport org.owasp.esapi.Encoder;\ncreateQuery(\"select * from User where id = '\" + Encoder.encodeForSQL(inputId) + \"'\");\n```\n\n## In Context Remediation\n```\nVulnerable Query: \"SELECT key FROM jwt_keys WHERE id = '\" + (String) header.get(\"kid\") + \"'\"\nRemediated Query: ## Description\n\nThe SQL statement is built by concatenating the JWT header kid value directly into the query string. In Java, this allows attacker-controlled input to alter the SQL command before it reaches the database, which can expose signing keys or change query behavior.\n\nThis is especially risky in key resolution code because the kid header is supplied by the token sender and must not be trusted. The query should be rewritten to use a PreparedStatement with a bind parameter so the database treats the value strictly as data, not executable SQL.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for all database access, including reads that appear low risk. Treat JWT header fields such as kid as untrusted input and validate expected format before querying, for example by restricting length and allowed characters. Avoid building SQL with string concatenation, String.format, or template expansion. Apply least-privilege database permissions so the account used for key lookup can only read the required table and columns.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~java\nString kid = (String) header.get(\"kid\");\nString sql = \"SELECT key FROM jwt_keys WHERE id = ?\";\n\ntry (PreparedStatement ps = connection.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n    ps.setString(1, kid);\n    try (ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) {\n        if (rs.next()) {\n            return rs.getBytes(\"key\");\n        }\n    }\n}\n\nthrow new SQLException(\"Signing key not found for provided kid\");\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~java\nimport java.sql.PreparedStatement;\nimport java.sql.ResultSet;\nimport java.sql.SQLException;\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Java PreparedStatement API](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/PreparedStatement.html)\n\n```\n#### Remediation\nBelow is a minimal **Java console** example showing the vulnerable query and the safe fix with a **prepared statement**.\n\n### `pom.xml` dependencies\n```xml\n<dependencies>\n  <!-- In-memory DB for reproducible demo -->\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    <version>2.2.224</version>\n  </dependency>\n\n  <!-- Optional logging -->\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>org.slf4j</groupId>\n    <artifactId>slf4j-simple</artifactId>\n    <version>2.0.13</version>\n  </dependency>\n</dependencies>\n```\n\n### `Main.java`\n```java\nimport java.sql.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        try (Connection c = DriverManager.getConnection(\"jdbc:h2:mem:test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1\")) {\n            setup(c);\n\n            String kid = \"abc' OR '1'='1\"; // attacker-controlled header.get(\"kid\")\n\n            System.out.println(\"Unsafe result: \" + unsafeLookup(c, kid));\n            System.out.println(\"Safe result:   \" + safeLookup(c, kid));\n        }\n    }\n\n    static void setup(Connection c) throws SQLException {\n        try (Statement s = c.createStatement()) {\n            s.execute(\"CREATE TABLE jwt_keys (id VARCHAR(50), key VARCHAR(50))\");\n            s.execute(\"INSERT INTO jwt_keys (id, key) VALUES ('abc', 'secret1')\");\n            s.execute(\"INSERT INTO jwt_keys (id, key) VALUES ('def', 'secret2')\");\n        }\n    }\n\n    // Vulnerable: like \"SELECT key FROM jwt_keys WHERE id = '\" + kid + \"'\"\n    static String unsafeLookup(Connection c, String kid) throws SQLException {\n        String sql = \"SELECT key FROM jwt_keys WHERE id = '\" + kid + \"'\";\n        try (Statement s = c.createStatement(); ResultSet rs = s.executeQuery(sql)) {\n            return rs.next() ? rs.getString(\"key\") : null;\n        }\n    }\n\n    // Safe: parameterized query / prepared statement\n    static String safeLookup(Connection c, String kid) throws SQLException {\n        String sql = \"SELECT key FROM jwt_keys WHERE id = ?\";\n        try (PreparedStatement ps = c.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n            ps.setString(1, kid);\n            try (ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) {\n                return rs.next() ? rs.getString(\"key\") : null;\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Why this prevents SQL injection\n`PreparedStatement` sends SQL and data separately, so malicious input in `kid` is treated as a literal string, not executable SQL.\n\n### Alternative JDBC drivers\n- PostgreSQL: `org.postgresql:postgresql`\n- MySQL: `com.mysql:mysql-connector-j`\n- MariaDB: `org.mariadb.jdbc:mariadb-java-client`\n- SQLite: `org.xerial:sqlite-jdbc`\n- Microsoft SQL Server: `com.microsoft.sqlserver:mssql-jdbc`\n- Oracle: `com.oracle.database.jdbc:ojdbc11`\n\n___\n\n\n**References (SQL injection)**\n\n- [CAPEC-66: SQL Injection](https://capec.mitre.org/data/definitions/66.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [OWASP: Top 10 A03_2021-Injection](https://owasp.org/Top10/A03_2021-Injection/)\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet)\n- [OWASP: Query Parameterization Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Query_Parameterization_Cheat_Sheet)\n\n\n"
              },
