              "id": "38f3cdba-3a19-37b1-b060-467ab53aae05",
              "name": "Unsafe Hash Equals",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure Hash Equality vulnerability in Java refers to the use of weak or insecure cryptographic hash functions for password storage or comparison. In the provided code snippet, MD5 and SHA-256 hash functions are used. MD5 is considered insecure due to its vulnerability to collision attacks, while SHA-256, although currently secure, is not recommended for password storage due to its speed, which makes it susceptible to brute force attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe general mitigation advice for this vulnerability is to use a strong and secure hash function for password storage. It is recommended to use a slow hash function that includes a salt, such as bcrypt, scrypt, or Argon2. These functions are designed to be slow and computationally expensive, which makes brute force attacks impractical.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the MD5 and SHA-256 hash functions with a secure hash function. Here is an example using bcrypt:\n\n```java\nimport org.mindrot.jbcrypt.BCrypt;\n\nString hashedPwd1 = BCrypt.hashpw(answer_pwd1, BCrypt.gensalt());\nString hashedPwd2 = BCrypt.hashpw(answer_pwd2, BCrypt.gensalt());\n\nif (BCrypt.checkpw(answer_pwd1, hashedPwd1) && BCrypt.checkpw(answer_pwd2, hashedPwd2)) {\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following library:\n\n- [jBcrypt](http://www.mindrot.org/projects/jBCrypt/)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-328: Reversible One-Way Hash](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/328.html)"
