            {
              "id": "3dff87f5-5d7a-31d4-87c7-d195d599f7d8",
              "name": "User Controlled Data Can Lead To XSS Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe XSS (Cross-Site Scripting) vulnerability risk in jQuery's `.append(...)` due to user-controlled data anti-pattern is a security flaw that allows an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. This vulnerability occurs when user-controlled data is directly passed into the `.append(...)` function. The injected script can access any cookies, session tokens, or other sensitive information retained by the browser and used with that site.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid directly passing user-controlled data into the `.append(...)` function. Instead, use text node creation or other safer methods to handle user-controlled data. Always validate and sanitize user input to ensure it does not contain any malicious code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly appending the user-controlled data, create a text node and append it:\n\n```javascript\nvar textNode = document.createTextNode(comment);\n$(\"#list\").append(textNode);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library to execute properly:\n\n- jQuery\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
