            {
              "id": "55776c2d-0900-3538-9b14-258a964c80fd",
              "name": "Potential JDBC Injection",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "\nThe input values included in SQL queries need to be passed in safely. Bind variables in prepared statements can be used to easily mitigate the risk of SQL injection. Alternatively to prepare statements, each parameter can be escaped manually.\n\n**Solution (Prepared Statements):**\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM User WHERE id = ?\";\nPreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npreparedStatement.setString(1, inputId);\nResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery();\n```\n\n**Solution (Encoding):**\n\n```java\nimport org.owasp.esapi.Encoder;\ncreateQuery(\"select * from User where id = '\" + Encoder.encodeForSQL(inputId) + \"'\");\n```\n\n## In Context Remediation\n```\nVulnerable Query: \"SELECT * FROM user_data WHERE first_name = 'John' and last_name = '\" + accountName + \"'\"\nRemediated Query: ## Description\n\nThis code builds a SQL statement by concatenating untrusted input directly into the query string. In Java, this allows an attacker to change the structure of the SQL command by supplying crafted values in accountName, which can bypass filters, return unauthorized data, or alter database behavior.\n\nThe fix is to use a PreparedStatement with bind parameters. Parameterized queries keep user input as data instead of executable SQL, which is the standard JDBC defense against SQL injection and is the correct remediation for this pattern.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nReplace all string-built SQL with PreparedStatement parameter binding, even when the value looks harmless. Validate input for expected format and length, but do not rely on validation or escaping as the primary defense. Use least-privileged database accounts so a successful injection has limited impact. Avoid exposing raw SQL errors to users, and review similar methods for the same concatenation pattern.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~java\nString sql = \"SELECT * FROM user_data WHERE first_name = ? AND last_name = ?\";\n\ntry (PreparedStatement pstmt = connection.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n    pstmt.setString(1, \"John\");\n    pstmt.setString(2, accountName);\n\n    try (ResultSet rs = pstmt.executeQuery()) {\n        while (rs.next()) {\n            // process results\n        }\n    }\n}\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~java\nimport java.sql.Connection;\nimport java.sql.PreparedStatement;\nimport java.sql.ResultSet;\nimport java.sql.SQLException;\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Oracle JDBC Tutorial: Using Prepared Statements](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/jdbc/basics/prepared.html)\n\n```\n#### Remediation\nBelow is a minimal **Java console** example showing the vulnerable query and the **safe fix with `PreparedStatement`**.\n\n### `pom.xml` dependencies\n```xml\n<dependencies>\n  <!-- In-memory DB for a reproducible demo -->\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    <version>2.2.224</version>\n  </dependency>\n</dependencies>\n```\n\n### `SqlInjectionPreventionDemo.java`\n```java\nimport java.sql.*;\n\npublic class SqlInjectionPreventionDemo {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        String url = \"jdbc:h2:mem:test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1\";\n\n        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url)) {\n            try (Statement st = con.createStatement()) {\n                st.execute(\"CREATE TABLE user_data (first_name VARCHAR(50), last_name VARCHAR(50))\");\n                st.execute(\"INSERT INTO user_data VALUES ('John','Smith'),('John','Doe'),('Jane','Doe')\");\n            }\n\n            String accountName = \"' OR '1'='1\"; // attacker input\n\n            // Vulnerable: string concatenation\n            String vulnerableSql =\n                \"SELECT * FROM user_data WHERE first_name = 'John' and last_name = '\" + accountName + \"'\";\n            try (Statement st = con.createStatement();\n                 ResultSet rs = st.executeQuery(vulnerableSql)) {\n                System.out.println(\"Vulnerable query results:\");\n                printRows(rs);\n            }\n\n            // Safe: prepared statement / parameterized query\n            String safeSql =\n                \"SELECT * FROM user_data WHERE first_name = ? and last_name = ?\";\n            try (PreparedStatement ps = con.prepareStatement(safeSql)) {\n                ps.setString(1, \"John\");\n                ps.setString(2, accountName);\n                try (ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) {\n                    System.out.println(\"PreparedStatement results:\");\n                    printRows(rs);\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    static void printRows(ResultSet rs) throws SQLException {\n        boolean found = false;\n        while (rs.next()) {\n            found = true;\n            System.out.println(rs.getString(\"first_name\") + \" \" + rs.getString(\"last_name\"));\n        }\n        if (!found) System.out.println(\"(no rows)\");\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n- **Vulnerable query**: may return multiple rows because injected input alters SQL logic.\n- **PreparedStatement**: treats input as data, so injection fails and likely returns **no rows**.\n\n### Alternative JDBC drivers\n- PostgreSQL: `org.postgresql:postgresql`\n- MySQL: `com.mysql:mysql-connector-j`\n- MariaDB: `org.mariadb.jdbc:mariadb-java-client`\n- SQLite: `org.xerial:sqlite-jdbc`\n- Microsoft SQL Server: `com.microsoft.sqlserver:mssql-jdbc`\n\n___\n\n\n**References (SQL injection)**\n\n- [CAPEC-66: SQL Injection](https://capec.mitre.org/data/definitions/66.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [OWASP: Top 10 A03_2021-Injection](https://owasp.org/Top10/A03_2021-Injection/)\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet)\n- [OWASP: Query Parameterization Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Query_Parameterization_Cheat_Sheet)\n\n\n"
              },
