              "id": "5fd9ef13-bfbf-3215-88f0-11cc571fcccb",
              "name": "Unsafe Hash Equals",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure Hash Equality Vulnerability in Java refers to the situation where a developer uses a weak or insecure hash function for comparing sensitive data, such as passwords or secret keys. This can lead to vulnerabilities where an attacker can generate a collision (two different inputs producing the same hash output), thus bypassing the security checks.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the developer is using the SHA-256 hash function, which is currently considered secure. However, the vulnerability could arise if a weaker hash function was used, or if the implementation of the hash comparison was flawed.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, developers should:\n\n1. Use a strong hash function. Currently, SHA-256 is considered secure, but this could change in the future as computational power increases and new attacks are discovered. Developers should stay updated on the latest cryptographic recommendations.\n\n2. Use a secure method for comparing hashes. The `equals()` method in Java is secure because it checks for both value and type equality. However, developers should be aware of timing attacks, where an attacker can gain information about the hash by measuring the time it takes to compare two hashes.\n\n3. Use a salt when hashing sensitive data. A salt is a random value that is added to the input of a hash function to prevent pre-computation attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code snippet is already using a secure hash function (SHA-256) and a secure comparison method (`equals()`). However, if the `getHash()` method does not use a salt, it should be modified to include one. Here is an example of how to add a salt to a SHA-256 hash in Java:\n\n```java\nimport java.security.SecureRandom;\nimport java.security.MessageDigest;\nimport java.util.Base64;\n\npublic class HashingAssignment {\n    private static final SecureRandom RANDOM = new SecureRandom();\n\n    public static String getHash(String secret, String algorithm) {\n        try {\n            MessageDigest md = MessageDigest.getInstance(algorithm);\n            byte[] salt = new byte[16];\n            RANDOM.nextBytes(salt);\n            md.update(salt);\n            byte[] hashedSecret = md.digest(secret.getBytes());\n            return Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(hashedSecret);\n        } catch (Exception e) {\n            throw new RuntimeException(e);\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following Java libraries:\n\n- `java.security.SecureRandom`\n- `java.security.MessageDigest`\n- `java.util.Base64`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-328: Reversible One-Way Hash](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/328.html)"
