            {
              "id": "63d868b2-fd3e-3b7d-89d8-c896bdbf3160",
              "name": "Improper Unicode Handling",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnicode Transformations Mismanagement Vulnerability in Java refers to the improper handling of Unicode transformations, which can lead to security vulnerabilities. This can occur when an application does not properly handle Unicode encoding during string comparison operations, such as the `equalsIgnoreCase()` method in Java. This can potentially allow an attacker to bypass security checks by using different Unicode representations of the same string.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a consistent Unicode normalization form throughout your application. Java provides the `java.text.Normalizer` class, which can be used to convert Unicode text into an equivalent composed or decomposed form, thus ensuring that text is compared in a consistent manner.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how you can normalize Unicode strings in Java:\n\n```java\nimport java.text.Normalizer;\nimport java.text.Normalizer.Form;\n\n// ...\n\nString usernameNormalized = Normalizer.normalize(username, Form.NFKC);\nif (usernameNormalized.equalsIgnoreCase(\"admin\")) {\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `Normalizer.normalize()` method is used to convert the `username` string into its composed form using the `Form.NFKC` normalization form. This ensures that the string is compared in a consistent manner, regardless of its original Unicode representation.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code example does not require any additional library dependencies, as the `java.text.Normalizer` class is part of the standard Java library.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-177: Improper Handling of Unicode Encoding](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/177.html)"
              },
