              "id": "7166835c-28ef-32b2-b601-7601b1e725af",
              "name": "Path Traversal Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA Path Traversal attack aims to access files and directories that are stored outside the web root folder. By manipulating variables that reference files with \"dot-dot-slash (../)\" sequences and its variations, or by using absolute file paths, it may be possible to access arbitrary files and directories stored on file system, including application source code, configuration, and critical system files.\n\nIn the provided Java code, the vulnerability lies in the fact that the user name is used to construct a file path. If the user name contains sequences like \"../\", it could lead to path traversal vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should validate and sanitize the user input. Avoid using user input directly in file path construction. If it's necessary to use user input, make sure to validate it strictly, for example, by checking against a whitelist of allowed values. Also, avoid disclosing sensitive information in error messages.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```java\nString userName = webSession.getUserName();\nif (userName.contains(\"../\") || userName.contains(\"..\\\\\")) {\n    throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"Invalid user name\");\n}\nnew File(webGoatHomeDirectory, \"/XXE/\" + userName + \"/secret.txt\");\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not provide enough context to determine the required library dependencies. However, it seems to be using some kind of web session object, which might be part of a web framework like Spring, Jakarta EE, etc.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Path Traversal](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Path_Traversal)\n- [CWE-22: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html)"
              },
