            {
              "id": "7ad3220f-9c06-32fb-966f-9a105827cb5e",
              "name": "Unsafe Hash Equals",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure Hash Equality vulnerability in Java refers to the use of insecure or weak cryptographic hash functions, such as MD5, for sensitive data. MD5 is considered insecure as it is susceptible to hash collisions, where two different inputs produce the same hash output, making it easier for attackers to guess the original input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a stronger hash function such as SHA-256 or SHA-3. Additionally, consider using a salt (a random value) that is added to the input of a hash function to protect against dictionary attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the MD5 hash function with a stronger one, such as SHA-256. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```java\nimport java.security.MessageDigest;\nimport java.security.NoSuchAlgorithmException;\nimport java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;\n\npublic class HashingAssignment {\n    public static String getHash(String input, String algorithm) throws NoSuchAlgorithmException {\n        MessageDigest digest = MessageDigest.getInstance(algorithm);\n        byte[] encodedhash = digest.digest(input.getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8));\n        return bytesToHex(encodedhash);\n    }\n\n    private static String bytesToHex(byte[] hash) {\n        StringBuilder hexString = new StringBuilder(2 * hash.length);\n        for (int i = 0; i < hash.length; i++) {\n            String hex = Integer.toHexString(0xff & hash[i]);\n            if(hex.length() == 1) hexString.append('0');\n            hexString.append(hex);\n        }\n        return hexString.toString();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAnd then use it like this:\n\n```java\nif (sha256Hash.equals(HashingAssignment.getHash(secret, \"SHA-256\"))) {\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It uses the `java.security.MessageDigest` and `java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets` classes, which are part of the standard Java library.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-328: Reversible One-Way Hash](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/328.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-328",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/328.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-328"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7b788701-f5b7-3f52-b07a-ff5f2a917144",
              "name": "Potential JDBC Injection (Spring JDBC)",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "\nThe input values included in SQL queries need to be passed in safely. Bind variables in prepared statements can be used to easily mitigate the risk of SQL injection. Alternatively to prepare statements, each parameter can be escaped manually.\n\n**Solution (Prepared Statements):**\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM User WHERE id = ?\";\nPreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npreparedStatement.setString(1, inputId);\nResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery();\n```\n\n**Solution (Encoding):**\n\n```java\nimport org.owasp.esapi.Encoder;\ncreateQuery(\"select * from User where id = '\" + Encoder.encodeForSQL(inputId) + \"'\");\n```\n\n## In Context Remediation\n```\nVulnerable Query: \"CREATE SCHEMA \\\"\" + webGoatUser.getUsername() + \"\\\" authorization dba\"\nRemediated Query: ## Description\n\nThis code constructs a SQL DDL statement by concatenating a username directly into the schema identifier. Even though the value is wrapped in double quotes, an attacker can still break the statement by supplying crafted input containing quote characters or other special syntax, leading to unauthorized SQL execution.\n\nIn Java, PreparedStatement protects data values, but schema names, table names, and other identifiers cannot be safely bound as ordinary parameters in most JDBC drivers. The fix is to enforce a strict allowlist for the identifier, reject invalid usernames, and only then compose the SQL from the validated value before executing it through JDBC.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not concatenate untrusted input into SQL statements. For Java JDBC code, use PreparedStatement for data values and apply strict allowlist validation when user input must become an SQL identifier such as a schema, table, or column name. Keep the allowed character set narrow, enforce a maximum length, and reject anything outside the expected format.\n\nIf user-controlled identifiers are unavoidable, consider mapping external usernames to internally generated safe schema names instead of using raw input directly. Also run the database connection with the least privileges necessary so that unexpected DDL execution cannot create or modify arbitrary database objects.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~java\nimport java.sql.Connection;\nimport java.sql.PreparedStatement;\nimport java.sql.SQLException;\nimport java.util.regex.Pattern;\n\nprivate static final Pattern SAFE_SCHEMA_NAME = Pattern.compile(\"^[A-Za-z0-9_]{1,30}$\");\n\nprivate void createLessonsForUser(WebGoatUser webGoatUser) throws SQLException {\n    String username = webGoatUser.getUsername();\n    if (username == null || !SAFE_SCHEMA_NAME.matcher(username).matches()) {\n        throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"Invalid schema name\");\n    }\n\n    String sql = \"CREATE SCHEMA \\\"\" + username + \"\\\" AUTHORIZATION dba\";\n    try (Connection connection = dataSource.getConnection();\n         PreparedStatement statement = connection.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n        statement.execute();\n    }\n}\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~java\njava.sql.Connection\njava.sql.PreparedStatement\njava.sql.SQLException\njava.util.regex.Pattern\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Java PreparedStatement API](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/PreparedStatement.html)\n\n```\n#### Remediation\nBelow is a minimal **Java console** example showing the unsafe pattern and a safer approach using **validation + quoted identifiers**.  \nNote: JDBC prepared statements generally **do not parameterize SQL identifiers** like schema names, only values. So for `CREATE SCHEMA <identifier>`, prevention requires **allowlisting/validation** before composing SQL.\n\n### `pom.xml` dependencies\n```xml\n<dependencies>\n  <!-- H2 in-memory DB for reproducible demo -->\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    <version>2.2.224</version>\n  </dependency>\n\n  <!-- Alternative drivers:\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>org.postgresql</groupId>\n    <artifactId>postgresql</artifactId>\n    <version>42.7.3</version>\n  </dependency>\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>com.mysql</groupId>\n    <artifactId>mysql-connector-j</artifactId>\n    <version>8.4.0</version>\n  </dependency>\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>org.xerial</groupId>\n    <artifactId>sqlite-jdbc</artifactId>\n    <version>3.46.1.3</version>\n  </dependency>\n  -->\n</dependencies>\n```\n\n### `Main.java`\n```java\nimport java.sql.*;\nimport java.util.regex.Pattern;\n\npublic class Main {\n    private static final Pattern SAFE_SCHEMA = Pattern.compile(\"[A-Za-z0-9_]{1,30}\");\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        try (Connection c = DriverManager.getConnection(\"jdbc:h2:mem:test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1\")) {\n            String bad = \"alice\\\" authorization dba; drop schema public cascade --\";\n            String good = \"alice_01\";\n\n            // Unsafe: vulnerable string concatenation\n            String unsafe = \"CREATE SCHEMA \\\"\" + bad + \"\\\" authorization dba\";\n            System.out.println(\"Unsafe SQL:\\n\" + unsafe);\n\n            // Safe: validate identifier, then quote it\n            createSchemaSafely(c, good);\n\n            // Example of real parameterization for VALUES\n            try (PreparedStatement ps =\n                    c.prepareStatement(\"INSERT INTO INFORMATION_SCHEMA.USERS(USER_NAME) VALUES (?)\")) {\n                ps.setString(1, \"demo\");\n                // illustrative only; may not be valid on all DBs/system tables\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    static void createSchemaSafely(Connection c, String username) throws SQLException {\n        if (!SAFE_SCHEMA.matcher(username).matches()) {\n            throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"Invalid schema name\");\n        }\n        String sql = \"CREATE SCHEMA \\\"\" + username + \"\\\" AUTHORIZATION DBA\";\n        try (Statement st = c.createStatement()) {\n            st.execute(sql);\n            System.out.println(\"Created schema safely: \" + username);\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Key point\n- **PreparedStatement**: use for **data values**.\n- **Schema/table/column names**: use **strict allowlist validation**; then safely quote according to your DB rules.\n\n___\n\n\n**References (SQL injection)**\n\n- [CAPEC-66: SQL Injection](https://capec.mitre.org/data/definitions/66.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [OWASP: Top 10 A03_2021-Injection](https://owasp.org/Top10/A03_2021-Injection/)\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet)\n- [OWASP: Query Parameterization Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Query_Parameterization_Cheat_Sheet)\n\n\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
