              "id": "7db55934-5d3b-3c58-bd6e-6ecf553f4e06",
              "name": "User Controlled Data In HTML String May Result In XSS",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet above is vulnerable to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. XSS is a type of injection, in which malicious scripts are injected into otherwise benign and trusted websites. In this case, the vulnerability arises from the fact that user-controlled data is directly used in an HTML string without proper sanitization or encoding. The `result` from the AJAX request is directly appended to the `#toast` element, which can lead to XSS if the `result` contains malicious scripts.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always encode user-controlled data before using it in an HTML context. This can be done using various methods, such as HTML entity encoding, JavaScript encoding, CSS encoding, URL encoding, etc., depending on the context in which the data is used.\n\nIn addition, you should also use Content Security Policy (CSP) to reduce the risk of XSS attacks. CSP provides a standard method for website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on their website.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nYou can fix the vulnerability in the code by encoding the `result` before appending it to the `#toast` element. Here is an example of how you can do this using jQuery's `text()` function, which automatically encodes the input:\n\n```javascript\n$.ajax({\n    type: 'POST',\n    url: 'JWT/final/follow/' + user\n}).then(function (result) {\n    $(\"#toast\").append($('<div>').text(result));\n});\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- jQuery\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
