            {
              "id": "87e33b69-bdd6-320d-9147-457905d222cb",
              "name": "Nonconstant string passed to execute or addBatch method on an SQL statement",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "\nThe input values included in SQL queries need to be passed in safely. Bind variables in prepared statements can be used to easily mitigate the risk of SQL injection. Alternatively to prepare statements, each parameter can be escaped manually.\n\n**Solution (Prepared Statements):**\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM User WHERE id = ?\";\nPreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npreparedStatement.setString(1, inputId);\nResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery();\n```\n\n**Solution (Encoding):**\n\n```java\nimport org.owasp.esapi.Encoder;\ncreateQuery(\"select * from User where id = '\" + Encoder.encodeForSQL(inputId) + \"'\");\n```\n\n## In Context Remediation\n```\nVulnerable Query: \"SET SCHEMA \\\"\" + (WebGoatUser) $obj0.getUsername() + \"\\\"\"\nRemediated Query: ## Description\n\nThis SQL fragment is built by concatenating a username directly into a statement that changes the database schema. In Java, constructing SQL from untrusted data allows an attacker to alter the command text and potentially switch to an unintended schema or execute a modified statement, depending on the database and driver behavior.\n\nEven when the value is placed inside quotes, string concatenation is not a safe defense for SQL commands. Schema names, table names, and other identifiers must not be taken directly from user-controlled input. The fix is to stop composing SQL with raw values and bind the value through a prepared statement, while also restricting the allowed schema names to a known-safe set or strict identifier pattern before execution.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse PreparedStatement for all SQL that accepts external input, and validate any value that represents a database identifier against a strict allowlist. Usernames and other request-derived values should never be used directly as schema, table, or column names.\n\nWhere the database does not support binding identifiers in a prepared statement, map user input to predefined schema names in application code and select from that mapping instead of inserting raw text into SQL. Keep database accounts scoped to the minimum required permissions so an unexpected schema change cannot escalate impact.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~java\nimport java.sql.Connection;\nimport java.sql.PreparedStatement;\nimport java.sql.SQLException;\nimport java.util.Set;\nimport java.util.regex.Pattern;\n\nprivate static final Pattern SCHEMA_NAME = Pattern.compile(\"^[A-Za-z0-9_]{1,30}$\");\nprivate static final Set<String> ALLOWED_SCHEMAS = Set.of(\"app\", \"training\", \"reporting\");\n\nprivate void setSchemaForUser(Connection connection, WebGoatUser user) throws SQLException {\n    String schema = user.getUsername();\n\n    if (schema == null || !SCHEMA_NAME.matcher(schema).matches() || !ALLOWED_SCHEMAS.contains(schema)) {\n        throw new SQLException(\"Invalid schema name\");\n    }\n\n    try (PreparedStatement statement = connection.prepareStatement(\"SET SCHEMA ?\")) {\n        statement.setString(1, schema);\n        statement.execute();\n    }\n}\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~java\nimport java.sql.Connection;\nimport java.sql.PreparedStatement;\nimport java.sql.SQLException;\nimport java.util.Set;\nimport java.util.regex.Pattern;\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Java PreparedStatement API](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.sql/java/sql/PreparedStatement.html)\n- [Java Connection API](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.sql/java/sql/Connection.html)\n\n```\n#### Remediation 1\nUse a whitelist for identifiers like schema names. Prepared statements only bind **values**, not SQL identifiers in most JDBC drivers, so `SET SCHEMA ?` often will not work. Safe pattern: validate the schema name, then quote it.\n\n```java\nimport java.sql.*;\nimport java.util.regex.Pattern;\n\npublic class SafeSetSchemaDemo {\n    private static final Pattern SAFE_SCHEMA = Pattern.compile(\"[A-Za-z0-9_]+\");\n\n    static void setSchemaSafely(Connection conn, String username) throws SQLException {\n        if (username == null || !SAFE_SCHEMA.matcher(username).matches()) {\n            throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"Invalid schema name\");\n        }\n        String sql = \"SET SCHEMA \\\"\" + username.replace(\"\\\"\", \"\\\"\\\"\") + \"\\\"\";\n        try (Statement st = conn.createStatement()) {\n            st.execute(sql);\n        }\n    }\n\n    static void preparedExampleForValues(Connection conn, String name) throws SQLException {\n        String sql = \"SELECT id, username FROM users WHERE username = ?\";\n        try (PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n            ps.setString(1, name);\n            try (ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) {\n                while (rs.next()) {\n                    System.out.println(rs.getInt(\"id\") + \": \" + rs.getString(\"username\"));\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        String url = \"jdbc:h2:mem:test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1\";\n        try (Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, \"sa\", \"\")) {\n            try (Statement st = conn.createStatement()) {\n                st.execute(\"CREATE SCHEMA safe_user\");\n                st.execute(\"CREATE TABLE users(id INT PRIMARY KEY, username VARCHAR(50))\");\n                st.execute(\"INSERT INTO users VALUES (1, 'alice')\");\n            }\n            setSchemaSafely(conn, \"safe_user\");\n            preparedExampleForValues(conn, \"alice\");\n            // setSchemaSafely(conn, \"safe_user\\\"; DROP TABLE users; --\"); // rejected\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n`pom.xml` dependency:\n```xml\n<dependencies>\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    <version>2.2.224</version>\n  </dependency>\n</dependencies>\n```\n\nAlternative JDBC drivers:\n- PostgreSQL: `org.postgresql:postgresql`\n- MySQL: `com.mysql:mysql-connector-j`\n- MariaDB: `org.mariadb.jdbc:mariadb-java-client`\n- SQLite: `org.xerial:sqlite-jdbc`\n\nKey point:\n- Original vulnerable code concatenates user input into `SET SCHEMA \"...\"`\n- For **data values**, use `PreparedStatement`\n- For **schema/table/column names**, use strict allowlisting + safe quoting\n\n#### Remediation 2\nBelow is a **minimal, reproducible Java console example** showing the unsafe pattern and a safer mitigation approach.\n\n> Note: many databases **do not allow bind parameters for identifiers** like schema names. In that case, use **allowlisting/validation** before composing the SQL.\n\n## `pom.xml` dependency\n```xml\n<dependencies>\n  <!-- PostgreSQL JDBC driver -->\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>org.postgresql</groupId>\n    <artifactId>postgresql</artifactId>\n    <version>42.7.3</version>\n  </dependency>\n</dependencies>\n```\n\n## `Main.java`\n```java\nimport java.sql.*;\nimport java.util.Set;\n\npublic class Main {\n    // Allowlist of valid schema names\n    private static final Set<String> ALLOWED_SCHEMAS =\n            Set.of(\"alice\", \"bob\", \"training\");\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        String url = \"jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/testdb\";\n        String user = \"test\";\n        String pass = \"test\";\n\n        String attackerInput = \"alice\\\"; DROP SCHEMA public CASCADE; --\";\n\n        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass)) {\n            // UNSAFE: string concatenation\n            String unsafeSql = \"SET SCHEMA \\\"\" + attackerInput + \"\\\"\";\n            System.out.println(\"UNSAFE SQL: \" + unsafeSql);\n\n            // SAFER: validate identifier, then use quoted composition\n            setSchemaSafely(con, \"alice\");\n\n            // If your DB supports it, parameterize data values, e.g.:\n            try (PreparedStatement ps =\n                         con.prepareStatement(\"SELECT current_schema() = ?\")) {\n                ps.setString(1, \"alice\");\n                try (ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) {\n                    while (rs.next()) {\n                        System.out.println(\"Schema match: \" + rs.getBoolean(1));\n                    }\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    static void setSchemaSafely(Connection con, String schema) throws SQLException {\n        if (!ALLOWED_SCHEMAS.contains(schema)) {\n            throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"Invalid schema\");\n        }\n        String safeSql = \"SET SCHEMA \\\"\" + schema.replace(\"\\\"\", \"\\\"\\\"\") + \"\\\"\";\n        try (Statement st = con.createStatement()) {\n            st.execute(safeSql);\n            System.out.println(\"SAFE SQL: \" + safeSql);\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Why this prevents injection\n- **Do not concatenate untrusted input** into SQL.\n- For **data values**, use `PreparedStatement`.\n- For **identifiers** (`SCHEMA`, table, column), use **strict allowlisting** because placeholders usually cannot bind identifiers.\n\n## Alternative JDBC drivers\n- MySQL: `com.mysql:mysql-connector-j`\n- MariaDB: `org.mariadb.jdbc:mariadb-java-client`\n- H2: `com.h2database:h2`\n- SQLite: `org.xerial:sqlite-jdbc`\n\n___\n\n\n**References (SQL injection)**\n\n- [CAPEC-66: SQL Injection](https://capec.mitre.org/data/definitions/66.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [OWASP: Top 10 A03_2021-Injection](https://owasp.org/Top10/A03_2021-Injection/)\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet)\n- [OWASP: Query Parameterization Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Query_Parameterization_Cheat_Sheet)\n\n\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "3.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "890fd572-2841-35d2-85b6-a1052e6be814",
              "name": "Predictable Secret Derived From Username or Email",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "Description\n-----------\nThe code snippet uses a deterministic transformation of a username (StringUtils.reverse(username)) as a password/reset token. Because the token is derived directly and reversibly from a publicly-known or guessable value (the username), an attacker who knows or can guess the username can trivially compute the token. This is a predictable password reset/token vulnerability that enables account takeover, unauthorized password resets, and other privilege escalation.\n\nWhy this is vulnerable\n- Tokens must be high-entropy and unpredictable. Reversing the username produces a token with no entropy beyond the username.\n- Usernames are often public, guessable, or enumerable.\n- Deterministic, reversible schemes provide no resistance to brute force, enumeration, or replay attacks.\n- The sink shown (StringUtils.reverse(username).equals(password)) accepts a predictable value as proof of identity.\n\nGeneral mitigation advice\n- Generate reset tokens using a cryptographically secure random generator (java.security.SecureRandom).\n- Make tokens long enough (e.g., 128+ bits / 16+ bytes; 256 bits recommended for extra margin).\n- Use URL-safe encoding (Base64 URL-safe, hex) when sending tokens in links.\n- Store only a one-way hash of the token in your database (e.g., SHA-256 or HMAC-SHA256 with a server-side secret) so the raw token is not persisted.\n- Mark tokens as single-use and revoke them immediately after successful use.\n- Set a short expiration time for tokens (e.g., 1 hour or less, based on risk).\n- Tie tokens to the account and context (user id, token purpose), and verify that the token presented matches the intended purpose and user.\n- Implement rate limiting / throttling on token verification endpoints to prevent brute force attempts.\n- Use constant-time comparison for token verification (MessageDigest.isEqual) to reduce timing attack risk.\n- Log token creation and usage events and alert on suspicious patterns (many failures, mass requests).\n- Require additional checks for high-risk flows (e.g., confirm via second factor or notify prior to change).\n\nSpecific source-code fix recommendation (replace the vulnerable sink)\n- Do not use StringUtils.reverse(username).equals(password) or any reversible/derivable transformation of a user attribute.\n- Generate a secure random token, send it to the user (via email), store only a secure hash of the token with expiration and one-time use flag, and verify presented tokens by hashing and comparing in constant time.\n\nExample Java implementation (generate, store hash, verify)\n```java\n// Dependencies: Java 8+ (java.security.SecureRandom, java.util.Base64, java.time.*)\n// Optional: Apache Commons Lang only if you need extra String utilities (NOT for token generation)\n\nimport java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;\nimport java.security.MessageDigest;\nimport java.security.NoSuchAlgorithmException;\nimport java.security.SecureRandom;\nimport java.time.Instant;\nimport java.util.Base64;\nimport java.util.Objects;\n\npublic class PasswordResetTokenService {\n    private static final SecureRandom SECURE_RANDOM = new SecureRandom();\n    private static final Base64.Encoder URL_ENCODER = Base64.getUrlEncoder().withoutPadding();\n    private static final Base64.Decoder URL_DECODER = Base64.getUrlDecoder();\n    private static final int TOKEN_BYTE_LENGTH = 32; // 256 bits\n\n    // Example model (replace with your DB/entity code)\n    public static class StoredToken {\n        public final String userId;\n        public final String tokenHashBase64; // store hash of token\n        public final Instant expiry;\n        public boolean used;\n\n        public StoredToken(String userId, String tokenHashBase64, Instant expiry) {\n            this.userId = userId;\n            this.tokenHashBase64 = tokenHashBase64;\n            this.expiry = expiry;\n            this.used = false;\n        }\n    }\n\n    // Generate a secure token (send rawToken to user via email link)\n    public static String generateRawToken() {\n        byte[] tokenBytes = new byte[TOKEN_BYTE_LENGTH];\n        SECURE_RANDOM.nextBytes(tokenBytes);\n        return URL_ENCODER.encodeToString(tokenBytes);\n    }\n\n    // Hash token for safe storage (SHA-256). Consider HMAC-SHA256 with server secret for extra protection.\n    public static String hashToken(String rawToken) {\n        try {\n            MessageDigest digest = MessageDigest.getInstance(\"SHA-256\");\n            byte[] hash = digest.digest(rawToken.getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8));\n            return Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(hash);\n        } catch (NoSuchAlgorithmException e) {\n            throw new IllegalStateException(\"SHA-256 not available\", e);\n        }\n    }\n\n    // Create and store token entry (example)\n    public StoredToken createAndStoreToken(String userId) {\n        Objects.requireNonNull(userId);\n        String rawToken = generateRawToken();\n        String hash = hashToken(rawToken);\n        Instant expiry = Instant.now().plusSeconds(60 * 60); // 1 hour expiry\n\n        StoredToken entry = new StoredToken(userId, hash, expiry);\n        // persist entry in DB and send rawToken to user via email:\n        // sendEmailWithTokenLink(userEmail, rawToken);\n        return entry; // return for example purposes (in real code do not log/send in clear)\n    }\n\n    // Verify presented token. Use constant-time comparison and check expiry/used flags.\n    public boolean verifyToken(String userId, String presentedRawToken, StoredToken stored) {\n        if (stored == null) return false;\n        if (!stored.userId.equals(userId)) return false;\n        if (stored.used) return false;\n        if (Instant.now().isAfter(stored.expiry)) return false;\n\n        String presentedHash = hashToken(presentedRawToken);\n        // constant-time comparison to avoid timing attacks:\n        boolean match = MessageDigest.isEqual(\n            presentedHash.getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8),\n            stored.tokenHashBase64.getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8)\n        );\n        if (match) {\n            stored.used = true; // mark single-use and persist change\n            return true;\n        }\n        return false;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIf you must use a deterministic or seeded value (not recommended), at minimum use HMAC with a server-side secret and include a nonce/timestamp and short expiry. But cryptographically-random one-time tokens are the preferred approach.\n\nFixing the specific vulnerable line\n- Replace:\n  && StringUtils.reverse(username).equals(password)) {\n- With a secure verification flow: look up the stored hashed token for the user, compute the hash of the presented token, compare using MessageDigest.isEqual, and enforce expiry/one-time use (see example above).\n\nLibrary dependencies required for the code example to execute properly\n- Java 8 or later (java.base packages: SecureRandom, MessageDigest, Base64, java.time)\n- No external libraries are required for the provided secure token code.\n- If your current project uses StringUtils.reverse, that method comes from Apache Commons Lang; the modern artifact is:\n  - org.apache.commons:commons-lang3:3.x (e.g., 3.12.0) — only needed if you use StringUtils elsewhere.\n\nMaven examples (if you use Apache Commons Lang elsewhere)\n```xml\n<!-- optional: only if you use org.apache.commons.lang3.StringUtils or other utilities -->\n<dependency>\n  <groupId>org.apache.commons</groupId>\n  <artifactId>commons-lang3</artifactId>\n  <version>3.12.0</version>\n</dependency>\n```\n\nRelevant resources\n- https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authentication_Cheat_Sheet.html\n- https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html\n- https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html\n- https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/330.html"
