            {
              "id": "8f9a6123-22bd-32db-99a1-7da170faa165",
              "name": "Original Filename Used In Path Construction",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "Description\n-----------\nPath traversal (also called directory traversal) is a vulnerability that occurs when an application uses untrusted input to construct file system paths without properly validating or canonicalizing that input. In Java web applications this commonly happens when a user-supplied filename (for example from MultipartFile.getOriginalFilename()) is used directly for filesystem access, upload storage, or to load files. An attacker can supply values such as \"../../secret.txt\" or an absolute path to read, overwrite, or delete files outside the intended directory.\n\nProblematic sink (example)\n--------------------------\nThe following line is unsafe if file.getOriginalFilename() is derived from user input and later used to access the filesystem:\n\nreturn super.execute(file, file.getOriginalFilename());\n\nAn attacker-controlled originalFilename may contain path traversal characters or absolute paths that allow access to files outside the allowed directory.\n\nGeneral mitigation advice\n-------------------------\n- Canonicalize and normalize paths before use (use java.nio.file.Path#normalize and toRealPath where appropriate).\n- Apply a whitelist (allow-list) for acceptable filenames or filename characters and enforce length limits.\n- Strip any path components from user-supplied names (e.g., keep only the basename).\n- Prefer server-generated filenames (UUIDs, monotonic ids) and map original filenames to those in a metadata store; do not use user-provided filenames directly for storage or execution.\n- Validate that the resolved target file is inside a known base directory: after resolving and normalizing, ensure targetPath.startsWith(baseDir).\n- Reject filenames that contain suspicious patterns (../, ..\\ , null bytes, absolute path prefixes).\n- Store uploaded files outside the webroot and configure least-privilege file permissions.\n- Minimize file handling privileges and use OS-level protections where possible (chroot, containerization).\n- Limit upload size and scan uploaded content for dangerous types.\n- Log and monitor unexpected filename or path-related errors.\n\nSource-code fix recommendation\n------------------------------\nBelow are two practical Java approaches. The first strips path components and validates the resulting name; the second generates a server-side filename and preserves (or maps) the client-provided name in metadata.\n\n1) Sanitize and validate the client filename, then call the sink with the safe name:\n\n```java\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.nio.file.Path;\nimport java.nio.file.Paths;\nimport java.util.UUID;\n\n// Example method in a class extending a parent that defines execute(MultipartFile, String)\n@Override\npublic Result execute(org.springframework.web.multipart.MultipartFile file) throws IOException {\n    if (file == null) {\n        throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"file required\");\n    }\n\n    // 1) Obtain original filename (may be null in some implementations)\n    String original = file.getOriginalFilename();\n    if (original == null || original.trim().isEmpty()) {\n        throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"invalid filename\");\n    }\n\n    // 2) Strip any path components (keeps only the basename)\n    String basename = Paths.get(original).getFileName().toString();\n\n    // 3) Whitelist-check: allow only safe characters and size limit\n    if (!basename.matches(\"^[A-Za-z0-9._-]{1,255}$\")) {\n        throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"filename contains invalid characters\");\n    }\n\n    // 4) Optionally, generate a server-side stable filename (recommended)\n    String extension = \"\";\n    int dot = basename.lastIndexOf('.');\n    if (dot >= 0) {\n        extension = basename.substring(dot); // includes the dot\n    }\n    String serverFilename = UUID.randomUUID().toString() + extension;\n\n    // 5) Use the safe server-generated filename for downstream operations\n    return super.execute(file, serverFilename);\n}\n```\n\nNotes:\n- Using Paths.get(original).getFileName().toString() removes any directory components supplied by the client.\n- The whitelist regex restricts allowed characters and prevents embedded traversal or control characters.\n- Generating a server-side filename (UUID) avoids relying on any client filename. Keep original filename only as metadata.\n\n2) If the next step in the code writes files, ensure the resolved path stays inside the allowed base directory:\n\n```java\nimport java.nio.file.Files;\nimport java.nio.file.Path;\nimport java.nio.file.StandardCopyOption;\n\nPath baseDir = Paths.get(\"/var/app/uploads\").toRealPath(); // ensure this exists and is owned appropriately\n\n// targetName is the serverFilename from above\nPath target = baseDir.resolve(serverFilename).normalize();\nif (!target.startsWith(baseDir)) {\n    throw new SecurityException(\"resolved path is outside the allowed directory\");\n}\n\n// Save uploaded file safely\ntry (var in = file.getInputStream()) {\n    Files.copy(in, target, StandardCopyOption.REPLACE_EXISTING);\n}\n```\n\nKey points:\n- Use toRealPath() / normalize() then check startsWith(baseDir) — this prevents traversal via symlinks or \"../\".\n- Do not call file names directly in OS commands; escape or avoid shell execution entirely.\n\nLibrary dependencies required\n-----------------------------\nThe code examples rely on the Java platform and (for typical web upload handling) Spring's MultipartFile. Minimum dependencies:\n\n- Java SE (JDK 8 or newer)\n  - java.nio.file.Path, Paths, Files, StandardCopyOption\n  - java.util.UUID\n- If using Spring MultipartFile in a web application:\n  - org.springframework:spring-web (or spring-webmvc) — for org.springframework.web.multipart.MultipartFile\n\nOptional (if you prefer library helpers):\n- commons-io:commons-io (Apache Commons IO) — for FilenameUtils.getName(...) as an alternative to Paths.get(...).getFileName()\n\nExample Maven coordinates:\n- Spring Web (if using Spring MVC's MultipartFile):\n  - org.springframework:spring-web:5.3.30 (or appropriate version for your Spring release)\n- Apache Commons IO (optional):\n  - commons-io:commons-io:2.11.0\n\nLinks\n-----\n- https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Path_Traversal\n- https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/File_Upload_Cheat_Sheet.html\n- https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "901e4024-1030-345f-91ab-1b9084c91d34",
              "name": "Potential JDBC Injection",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "\nThe input values included in SQL queries need to be passed in safely. Bind variables in prepared statements can be used to easily mitigate the risk of SQL injection. Alternatively to prepare statements, each parameter can be escaped manually.\n\n**Solution (Prepared Statements):**\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM User WHERE id = ?\";\nPreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npreparedStatement.setString(1, inputId);\nResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery();\n```\n\n**Solution (Encoding):**\n\n```java\nimport org.owasp.esapi.Encoder;\ncreateQuery(\"select * from User where id = '\" + Encoder.encodeForSQL(inputId) + \"'\");\n```\n\n## In Context Remediation\n```\nVulnerable Query: \"SELECT * FROM user_data WHERE last_name = '\" + accountName + \"'\"\nRemediated Query: ## Description\n\nThis code builds an SQL query by concatenating untrusted input directly into the statement text. In Java, this pattern allows an attacker to change the meaning of the query by supplying crafted values that break out of the string literal and append additional SQL.\n\nThe fix is to replace string concatenation with a parameterized query using PreparedStatement. Parameter binding sends the SQL structure and the user-supplied value separately, so the database treats the input strictly as data rather than executable SQL. This is the standard JDBC defense for SQL injection.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse PreparedStatement for every query that includes external input, including values from HTTP parameters, headers, cookies, and stored data. Do not assemble SQL with string concatenation, StringBuilder, or String.format when any part can be influenced by a user.\n\nIf table names, column names, or sort directions must vary, map the allowed options from a fixed application-controlled allowlist instead of accepting raw input. Also run the application with the minimum required database privileges so that a successful injection has limited impact.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~java\nString sql = \"SELECT * FROM user_data WHERE last_name = ?\";\n\ntry (Connection connection = dataSource.getConnection();\n     PreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n    preparedStatement.setString(1, accountName);\n\n    try (ResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery()) {\n        while (resultSet.next()) {\n            // process results\n        }\n    }\n}\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~java\nimport java.sql.Connection;\nimport java.sql.PreparedStatement;\nimport java.sql.ResultSet;\nimport java.sql.SQLException;\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Java PreparedStatement API](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/PreparedStatement.html)\n\n```\n#### Remediation\nBelow is a minimal **Java console** example showing the vulnerable pattern and the safe fix with a **prepared statement**.\n\n### `pom.xml` dependencies\n```xml\n<dependencies>\n  <!-- JDBC driver for SQLite -->\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>org.xerial</groupId>\n    <artifactId>sqlite-jdbc</artifactId>\n    <version>3.46.1.3</version>\n  </dependency>\n</dependencies>\n```\n\n### `Main.java`\n```java\nimport java.sql.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n  public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n    String url = \"jdbc:sqlite::memory:\";\n\n    try (Connection c = DriverManager.getConnection(url)) {\n      setup(c);\n\n      String accountName = \"Smith' OR '1'='1\";\n\n      System.out.println(\"Vulnerable query:\");\n      vulnerableQuery(c, accountName);\n\n      System.out.println(\"\\nSafe query:\");\n      safeQuery(c, accountName);\n    }\n  }\n\n  static void setup(Connection c) throws SQLException {\n    try (Statement s = c.createStatement()) {\n      s.executeUpdate(\"CREATE TABLE user_data (id INTEGER, last_name TEXT)\");\n      s.executeUpdate(\"INSERT INTO user_data VALUES (1, 'Smith')\");\n      s.executeUpdate(\"INSERT INTO user_data VALUES (2, 'Jones')\");\n    }\n  }\n\n  static void vulnerableQuery(Connection c, String accountName) throws SQLException {\n    String sql = \"SELECT * FROM user_data WHERE last_name = '\" + accountName + \"'\";\n    System.out.println(sql);\n    try (Statement s = c.createStatement();\n         ResultSet rs = s.executeQuery(sql)) {\n      print(rs);\n    }\n  }\n\n  static void safeQuery(Connection c, String accountName) throws SQLException {\n    String sql = \"SELECT * FROM user_data WHERE last_name = ?\";\n    System.out.println(sql + \" [param=\" + accountName + \"]\");\n    try (PreparedStatement ps = c.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n      ps.setString(1, accountName);\n      try (ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) {\n        print(rs);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  static void print(ResultSet rs) throws SQLException {\n    while (rs.next()) {\n      System.out.println(\"id=\" + rs.getInt(\"id\")\n          + \", last_name=\" + rs.getString(\"last_name\"));\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Why this prevents SQL injection\nThe unsafe version concatenates input into:\n```java\n\"SELECT * FROM user_data WHERE last_name = '\" + accountName + \"'\"\n```\nA prepared statement keeps SQL and data separate, so input is treated as a literal value, not executable SQL.\n\n### Alternative JDBC drivers\n```xml\n<!-- PostgreSQL -->\n<dependency>\n  <groupId>org.postgresql</groupId>\n  <artifactId>postgresql</artifactId>\n  <version>42.7.3</version>\n</dependency>\n\n<!-- MySQL -->\n<dependency>\n  <groupId>com.mysql</groupId>\n  <artifactId>mysql-connector-j</artifactId>\n  <version>9.0.0</version>\n</dependency>\n\n<!-- H2 -->\n<dependency>\n  <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n  <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n  <version>2.3.232</version>\n</dependency>\n```\n\n___\n\n\n**References (SQL injection)**\n\n- [CAPEC-66: SQL Injection](https://capec.mitre.org/data/definitions/66.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [OWASP: Top 10 A03_2021-Injection](https://owasp.org/Top10/A03_2021-Injection/)\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet)\n- [OWASP: Query Parameterization Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Query_Parameterization_Cheat_Sheet)\n\n\n"
              },
