            {
              "id": "90e8cc40-934f-3ce2-a630-9de26b443a27",
              "name": "Potential JDBC Injection",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "\nThe input values included in SQL queries need to be passed in safely. Bind variables in prepared statements can be used to easily mitigate the risk of SQL injection. Alternatively to prepare statements, each parameter can be escaped manually.\n\n**Solution (Prepared Statements):**\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM User WHERE id = ?\";\nPreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npreparedStatement.setString(1, inputId);\nResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery();\n```\n\n**Solution (Encoding):**\n\n```java\nimport org.owasp.esapi.Encoder;\ncreateQuery(\"select * from User where id = '\" + Encoder.encodeForSQL(inputId) + \"'\");\n```\n\n## In Context Remediation\n```\nVulnerable Query: \"SELECT * FROM access_log WHERE action LIKE '%\" + action + \"%'\"\nRemediated Query: ## Description\n\nThe SQL statement is built by concatenating untrusted input directly into the query string. In Java JDBC code, this allows attacker-controlled characters to change the structure of the SQL command instead of being treated only as data.\n\nFor a LIKE search, string concatenation is still unsafe even when percent signs are added around the value. An attacker can inject quotes, wildcards, or SQL operators through the action parameter. Use a PreparedStatement and bind the search term as a parameter so the database parses SQL and data separately.\n\nIf wildcard behavior is intended, construct the pattern in Java and pass it as the bound parameter value. This preserves the search feature while preventing SQL injection.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nReplace all dynamically concatenated SQL with parameterized queries throughout the codebase. In JDBC, use PreparedStatement for every variable value, including values used with LIKE, IN, and numeric filters. Do not rely on manual escaping or input filtering as the primary defense.\n\nWhere wildcard characters should be treated literally, escape % and _ according to the database dialect and add an ESCAPE clause. Apply least-privilege database accounts so a successful injection has limited impact, and avoid exposing detailed SQL errors to users.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~java\nString sql = \"SELECT * FROM access_log WHERE action LIKE ?\";\n\ntry (PreparedStatement pstmt = connection.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n    pstmt.setString(1, \"%\" + action + \"%\");\n\n    try (ResultSet rs = pstmt.executeQuery()) {\n        // process results\n    }\n}\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~java\nimport java.sql.PreparedStatement;\nimport java.sql.ResultSet;\nimport java.sql.SQLException;\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Java PreparedStatement API](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/PreparedStatement.html)\n- [Using Prepared Statements (JDBC Tutorial)](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/jdbc/basics/prepared.html)\n\n```\n#### Remediation\nBelow is a minimal **Java console** example showing the unsafe query and the **safe prepared-statement version**.\n\n### `pom.xml` dependencies\n```xml\n<dependencies>\n    <!-- H2 in-memory database -->\n    <dependency>\n        <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n        <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n        <version>2.2.224</version>\n    </dependency>\n</dependencies>\n```\n\n### `Main.java`\n```java\nimport java.sql.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        String url = \"jdbc:h2:mem:test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1\";\n\n        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url)) {\n            try (Statement st = con.createStatement()) {\n                st.execute(\"CREATE TABLE access_log(id INT PRIMARY KEY, action VARCHAR(255))\");\n                st.execute(\"INSERT INTO access_log VALUES (1, 'login'), (2, 'logout'), (3, 'admin-view')\");\n            }\n\n            String action = \"' OR '1'='1\"; // attacker-controlled input\n\n            // Unsafe: vulnerable to SQL injection\n            String vulnerableSql =\n                \"SELECT * FROM access_log WHERE action LIKE '%\" + action + \"%'\";\n            try (Statement st = con.createStatement();\n                 ResultSet rs = st.executeQuery(vulnerableSql)) {\n                System.out.println(\"Unsafe query: \" + vulnerableSql);\n                while (rs.next()) {\n                    System.out.println(\"UNSAFE -> \" + rs.getInt(\"id\") + \": \" + rs.getString(\"action\"));\n                }\n            }\n\n            // Safe: parameterized query / prepared statement\n            String safeSql = \"SELECT * FROM access_log WHERE action LIKE ?\";\n            try (PreparedStatement ps = con.prepareStatement(safeSql)) {\n                ps.setString(1, \"%\" + action + \"%\");\n                try (ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) {\n                    System.out.println(\"\\nSafe query: \" + safeSql + \" [param=%\" + action + \"%]\");\n                    while (rs.next()) {\n                        System.out.println(\"SAFE -> \" + rs.getInt(\"id\") + \": \" + rs.getString(\"action\"));\n                    }\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Why this prevents injection\n`PreparedStatement` sends SQL and data separately. The user input is treated as a **value**, not executable SQL, so payloads like `\"' OR '1'='1\"` cannot alter query logic.\n\n### Alternative JDBC drivers\n- PostgreSQL: `org.postgresql:postgresql`\n- MySQL: `com.mysql:mysql-connector-j`\n- MariaDB: `org.mariadb.jdbc:mariadb-java-client`\n- SQLite: `org.xerial:sqlite-jdbc`\n- Microsoft SQL Server: `com.microsoft.sqlserver:mssql-jdbc`\n\n___\n\n\n**References (SQL injection)**\n\n- [CAPEC-66: SQL Injection](https://capec.mitre.org/data/definitions/66.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [OWASP: Top 10 A03_2021-Injection](https://owasp.org/Top10/A03_2021-Injection/)\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet)\n- [OWASP: Query Parameterization Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Query_Parameterization_Cheat_Sheet)\n\n\n"
              },
