            {
              "id": "9b12f65f-899b-3a40-a69e-9cf21f2d9bc0",
              "name": "Potential Path Traversal (file read)",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "\nA path traversal attack (also known as directory traversal) aims to access files and directories that are stored outside the web root folder. By manipulating variables that reference files with “dot-dot-slash (../)” sequences and its variations or by using absolute file paths, it may be possible to access arbitrary files and directories stored on file system including application source code or configuration and critical system files.\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability in Java, you can use path canonicalization and ensure that the resolved path is within a designated base directory. \n\n## Solution (Path Canonicalization)\n\n```java\n\n    // Base directory where files are allowed to be accessed\n    private static final String BASE_DIRECTORY = \"/safe/base/directory\";\n\n        /**\n         * Resolves the user input to a secure file path within the base directory.\n         *\n         * @param userInput The user-provided file path.\n         * @return A File object if the path is valid and within the base directory, otherwise null.\n         * @throws IOException If an error occurs during path resolution.\n         */\n        public static File getSecureFile(String userInput) throws IOException {\n            // Create a file object from the user input\n            File file = new File(BASE_DIRECTORY, userInput);\n\n            // Canonicalize the file path\n            String canonicalPath = file.getCanonicalPath();\n\n            // Check if the canonical path starts with the base directory path\n            if (canonicalPath.startsWith(new File(BASE_DIRECTORY).getCanonicalPath())) {\n                return file;\n            } else {\n                // The path is outside the base directory, deny access\n                return null;\n            }\n        }\n\n```\n\n## In Context Remediation\n```\nPath construction: new File(fileLocation, username)\nPath canonicalization: ## Description\n\nBuilding a file path from a base directory and a user-influenced value such as username can allow path traversal if the resulting path is used without canonicalization and a directory containment check. In Java, sequences like .., absolute paths, or symbolic links can cause the resolved file to point outside the intended storage directory.\n\nThe fix is to resolve the untrusted path against a trusted base directory, canonicalize the result, and verify that the canonical target still starts with the canonical base path before accessing the file. This ensures the application only serves files from the expected directory tree.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTreat any path component derived from request data, user names, headers, or database values as untrusted. Use java.nio.file.Path to resolve paths from a trusted base directory, canonicalize with toRealPath when the path must exist, and reject any resolved path that does not remain under the intended base directory. Avoid string concatenation for filesystem paths, and consider additionally restricting allowed characters in directory or file names to a safe whitelist.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~java\nPath basePath = Paths.get(fileLocation).toRealPath();\nPath requestedPath = basePath.resolve(username).normalize();\nPath canonicalRequestedPath = requestedPath.toRealPath();\n\nif (!canonicalRequestedPath.startsWith(basePath)) {\n    throw new AccessDeniedException(\"Invalid file path\");\n}\n\nFile userDirectory = canonicalRequestedPath.toFile();\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~java\nimport java.io.File;\nimport java.nio.file.AccessDeniedException;\nimport java.nio.file.Path;\nimport java.nio.file.Paths;\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Path Traversal](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Path_Traversal)\n- [CWE-22: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html)\n- [Java Path.normalize() API](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/nio/file/Path.html#normalize())\n- [Java Path.toRealPath() API](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/nio/file/Path.html#toRealPath(java.nio.file.LinkOption...))\n\n```\n#### Remediation\n```java\npackage demo;\n\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.nio.file.Files;\nimport java.nio.file.Path;\nimport java.nio.file.Paths;\n\npublic class SecurePathDemo {\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        String fileLocation = \"/var/webwolf/uploads\";\n        String username = args.length > 0 ? args[0] : \"alice\";\n\n        try {\n            Path safeUserDir = resolveUserDirectory(fileLocation, username);\n            System.out.println(\"Validated path: \" + safeUserDir);\n\n            if (Files.exists(safeUserDir)) {\n                System.out.println(\"Directory exists.\");\n            } else {\n                System.out.println(\"Directory does not exist.\");\n            }\n        } catch (SecurityException | IOException e) {\n            System.err.println(\"Path validation failed: \" + e.getMessage());\n        }\n    }\n\n    public static Path resolveUserDirectory(String fileLocation, String username) throws IOException {\n        if (fileLocation == null || username == null) {\n            throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"fileLocation and username must not be null\");\n        }\n\n        Path baseDir = Paths.get(fileLocation).toRealPath().normalize();\n\n        Path candidate = baseDir.resolve(username).normalize();\n\n        Path canonicalCandidate;\n        if (Files.exists(candidate)) {\n            canonicalCandidate = candidate.toRealPath().normalize();\n        } else {\n            Path parent = candidate.getParent();\n            if (parent == null) {\n                throw new SecurityException(\"Invalid path\");\n            }\n            Path canonicalParent = parent.toRealPath().normalize();\n            canonicalCandidate = canonicalParent.resolve(candidate.getFileName()).normalize();\n        }\n\n        if (!canonicalCandidate.startsWith(baseDir)) {\n            throw new SecurityException(\"Resolved path escapes base directory\");\n        }\n\n        return canonicalCandidate;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### What this fixes\nThis securely replaces logic like:\n```java\nnew File(fileLocation, username)\n```\nby:\n1. Canonicalizing the trusted base directory.\n2. Resolving the untrusted `username` against it.\n3. Canonicalizing the result.\n4. Verifying the final path still starts with the intended base directory.\n\nThis prevents path traversal such as `../admin` and symlink-based escapes.\n\n### Imports included\n- `java.io.IOException`\n- `java.nio.file.Files`\n- `java.nio.file.Path`\n- `java.nio.file.Paths`\n\n### Dependencies\nOnly the Java standard library is required.\n\nFor Maven:\n```xml\n<project xmlns=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0\"\n         xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"\n         xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd\">\n    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>\n    <groupId>demo</groupId>\n    <artifactId>secure-path-demo</artifactId>\n    <version>1.0.0</version>\n    <properties>\n        <maven.compiler.source>17</maven.compiler.source>\n        <maven.compiler.target>17</maven.compiler.target>\n    </properties>\n</project>\n```\n\n### Compile and run\n```bash\nmvn compile\njava -cp target/classes demo.SecurePathDemo alice\n```\n\n___\n\n\n## References\n- [OWASP: Path Traversal](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Path_Traversal)\n- [OWASP: Input Validation Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Input_Validation_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-22: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html)\n\n\n"
