            {
              "id": "a7b11218-8ea7-31dd-aa8e-49073e73f6aa",
              "name": "Unsafe Hash Equals",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure Hash Equality Vulnerability in Java refers to the situation where a system uses a weak or insecure cryptographic hash function to protect sensitive data. This can lead to a variety of security issues, such as collision attacks, where an attacker can generate the same hash from different inputs, thereby bypassing security controls.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the system is comparing the user-provided hash (`userHash`) with the stored hash (`displayUser.getUserHash()`). If a weak hash function is used, an attacker could potentially provide a different input that produces the same hash, thereby impersonating a legitimate user.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a strong, collision-resistant hash function. Additionally, it is also recommended to use a salt (a random value that is used as an additional input to the hash function) to further increase the security of the hash. The salt should be unique per user and should be stored alongside the hash.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```java\nimport java.security.MessageDigest;\nimport java.security.NoSuchAlgorithmException;\nimport java.security.SecureRandom;\n\n// ...\n\nSecureRandom random = new SecureRandom();\nbyte[] salt = new byte[16];\nrandom.nextBytes(salt);\n\nMessageDigest md = MessageDigest.getInstance(\"SHA-256\");\nmd.update(salt);\nbyte[] hashedPassword = md.digest(userPassword.getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8));\n\nif (Arrays.equals(hashedPassword, displayUser.getHashedPassword())) {\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, we're using the SHA-256 hash function, which is currently considered to be secure. We're also using a salt to increase the security of the hash.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n- `java.security.MessageDigest`\n- `java.security.NoSuchAlgorithmException`\n- `java.security.SecureRandom`\n- `java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets`\n- `java.util.Arrays`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-328: Reversible One-Way Hash](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/328.html)"
              },
