            {
              "id": "adbcfce8-5d0a-34a2-ba1b-c7b0ecfec6dd",
              "name": "Spring Endpoint",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Found Spring endpoint\" vulnerability refers to the exposure of sensitive information or functionality through the endpoints of a Spring application. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access to sensitive data or functionality, potentially leading to further attacks such as SQL injection, Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), or Remote Code Execution (RCE).\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to:\n\n1. Limit the exposure of endpoints: Only expose the necessary endpoints and keep the rest hidden or inaccessible.\n\n2. Implement proper authentication and authorization: Ensure that only authenticated and authorized users can access the exposed endpoints.\n\n3. Validate and sanitize input: Always validate and sanitize input from users to prevent injection attacks.\n\n4. Use HTTPS: Use HTTPS to encrypt the communication between the client and the server, preventing Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple example of how to secure a Spring endpoint:\n\n```java\n@RestController\n@RequestMapping(\"/api\")\npublic class SecureController {\n\n    @Autowired\n    private AuthenticationManager authenticationManager;\n\n    @PostMapping(\"/authenticate\")\n    public ResponseEntity<?> createAuthenticationToken(@RequestBody AuthenticationRequest authenticationRequest) throws Exception {\n        try {\n            authenticationManager.authenticate(\n                    new UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken(authenticationRequest.getUsername(), authenticationRequest.getPassword())\n            );\n        } catch (BadCredentialsException e) {\n            throw new Exception(\"Incorrect username or password\", e);\n        }\n\n        // Continue with the creation of JWT token and other necessary steps...\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `/authenticate` endpoint is secured by checking the provided username and password. If the authentication fails, an exception is thrown.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: A6-Security Misconfiguration](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A6_2017-Security_Misconfiguration)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-200: Information Exposure](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html)\n- [CWE-285: Improper Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/285.html)"
