              "id": "b1319303-c1ef-3be9-be06-225b852eb82c",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Written To Application Log",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure in Application Log is a vulnerability that occurs when an application unintentionally exposes sensitive data in its logs. In the provided Java code, the application is logging an encoded version of an admin password. Even though the password is encoded, it is still considered sensitive data and should not be logged. This could lead to unauthorized access if the logs are not properly secured or if they are leaked.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, sensitive data such as passwords should never be logged, even in an encoded form. If there is a need to log data for debugging purposes, make sure to remove any sensitive data before logging. Also, ensure that your logs are properly secured and monitored for any unauthorized access.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code:\n\n```java\n// Do not log sensitive data\nlog.info(\"Admin password updated successfully\");\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Java Standard Edition (SE) 8 or later\n- A logging framework that supports the `info` method, such as SLF4J or Log4j\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A3:2017-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-532: Information Exposure Through Log Files](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/532.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
