            {
              "id": "b1a876b3-3d7f-3415-8abe-52be3d9f9d36",
              "name": "User Controlled Data In HTML String May Result In XSS",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA potential Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is used in an HTML string. In the provided JavaScript code, the `result` variable is concatenated to a string that is then used to set the `src` attribute of an HTML element. If an attacker can control the value of `result`, they could inject malicious scripts that would be executed in the context of the user's session.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always sanitize user-controlled data before using it in an HTML context. This can be done by using a library that provides HTML encoding functions, or by using built-in JavaScript functions like `encodeURIComponent()`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code:\n\n```javascript\ndocument.getElementById(\"preview\").src = \"data:image/png;base64,\" + encodeURIComponent(result);\n```\n\nIn this fix, the `encodeURIComponent()` function is used to encode the `result` variable. This ensures that any special characters in `result` are properly escaped, preventing them from being interpreted as part of the HTML.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any library dependencies. It uses only built-in JavaScript functions and properties.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
