            {
              "id": "b8c6b091-a21c-3d27-94ce-d6f57f687b48",
              "name": "User Data Flows Into Host Portion Of URL",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nServer-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) is a type of vulnerability that allows an attacker to force a server to make requests on their behalf. In the context of Java programming, this vulnerability can occur when a URL is manually constructed and used to create a new `JwkProvider` object. If the URL is constructed from user-supplied input (`jku.asString()` in this case), an attacker could potentially control the destination of the request, leading to unauthorized access to internal resources, information disclosure, or other potential attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using user-supplied input to construct URLs whenever possible. If it is necessary to use user-supplied input, the input should be properly validated and sanitized to ensure it does not contain malicious values. Additionally, network-level controls should be implemented to restrict the server from making requests to unauthorized or sensitive internal resources.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```java\n// Import necessary libraries\nimport java.net.URL;\nimport com.auth0.jwk.JwkProvider;\nimport com.auth0.jwk.JwkProviderBuilder;\n\n// Assume jku is a user-supplied input\nString jkuInput = jku.asString();\n\n// Validate and sanitize the jkuInput before using it to construct a URL\nif (isValidURL(jkuInput)) {\n    URL url = new URL(jkuInput);\n    JwkProvider jwkProvider = new JwkProviderBuilder(url).build();\n} else {\n    // Handle invalid URL input\n}\n\n// Method to validate a URL\npublic boolean isValidURL(String url) {\n    // Implement URL validation logic here\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n- `java.net.URL`: Part of Java's standard library, used for working with URLs.\n- `com.auth0.jwk.JwkProvider` and `com.auth0.jwk.JwkProviderBuilder`: Part of the Auth0 Java-JWT library, used for working with JSON Web Tokens (JWTs).\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Server_Side_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-918: Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/918.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-918",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/918.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-918"
                ]
              }
