            {
              "id": "c4cbe522-cf83-38ca-9cef-eabb5e7322b1",
              "name": "Potential JDBC Injection",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "\nThe input values included in SQL queries need to be passed in safely. Bind variables in prepared statements can be used to easily mitigate the risk of SQL injection. Alternatively to prepare statements, each parameter can be escaped manually.\n\n**Solution (Prepared Statements):**\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM User WHERE id = ?\";\nPreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npreparedStatement.setString(1, inputId);\nResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery();\n```\n\n**Solution (Encoding):**\n\n```java\nimport org.owasp.esapi.Encoder;\ncreateQuery(\"select * from User where id = '\" + Encoder.encodeForSQL(inputId) + \"'\");\n```\n\n## In Context Remediation\n```\nVulnerable Query: \"select userid from sql_challenge_users where userid = '\" + username_reg + \"'\"\nRemediated Query: ## Description\n\nThis code builds an SQL query by concatenating untrusted request data directly into the statement. In Java, this allows an attacker to change the meaning of the query by supplying crafted input that closes the string literal and injects additional SQL.\n\nThe fix is to use a PreparedStatement with bind parameters so the JDBC driver sends the SQL structure separately from the user-supplied values. This preserves the intended query logic and prevents input from being interpreted as executable SQL.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nReplace all SQL string concatenation that includes request parameters, form fields, headers, cookies, or database-derived text with parameterized queries. Apply this consistently to SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, and stored procedure calls. Validate input for business rules such as length and allowed characters, but do not rely on validation alone as a defense against SQL injection.\n\nUse least-privilege database accounts so a successful injection cannot access or modify unnecessary data. Avoid dynamic SQL where possible, and when dynamic identifiers such as column names or sort directions are required, select them from a fixed allowlist in application code before constructing the statement.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~java\nString sql = \"select userid from sql_challenge_users where userid = ?\";\n\ntry (Connection connection = dataSource.getConnection();\n     PreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n    preparedStatement.setString(1, username_reg);\n\n    try (ResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery()) {\n        if (resultSet.next()) {\n            String userId = resultSet.getString(\"userid\");\n            // handle existing user\n        }\n    }\n}\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~java\nimport java.sql.Connection;\nimport java.sql.PreparedStatement;\nimport java.sql.ResultSet;\nimport javax.sql.DataSource;\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Oracle JDBC Tutorial: Using Prepared Statements](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/jdbc/basics/prepared.html)\n\n```\n#### Remediation\nBelow is a minimal **Java console** example showing the vulnerable pattern and the safe **PreparedStatement** fix.\n\n### `pom.xml` dependencies\n```xml\n<dependencies>\n  <!-- In-memory demo DB -->\n  <dependency>\n    <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    <version>2.2.224</version>\n    <scope>runtime</scope>\n  </dependency>\n</dependencies>\n```\n\n### `SqlInjectionPreparedStatementDemo.java`\n```java\nimport java.sql.*;\n\npublic class SqlInjectionPreparedStatementDemo {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        String url = \"jdbc:h2:mem:test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1\";\n\n        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url, \"sa\", \"\")) {\n            setup(con);\n\n            String username_reg = \"tom' OR '1'='1\";\n\n            // Vulnerable\n            String vulnerableSql =\n                \"select userid from sql_challenge_users where userid = '\" + username_reg + \"'\";\n            try (Statement st = con.createStatement();\n                 ResultSet rs = st.executeQuery(vulnerableSql)) {\n                System.out.println(\"VULNERABLE query: \" + vulnerableSql);\n                while (rs.next()) {\n                    System.out.println(\"Matched userid: \" + rs.getString(\"userid\"));\n                }\n            }\n\n            // Safe\n            String safeSql =\n                \"select userid from sql_challenge_users where userid = ?\";\n            try (PreparedStatement ps = con.prepareStatement(safeSql)) {\n                ps.setString(1, username_reg);\n                try (ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) {\n                    System.out.println(\"SAFE query with parameter: \" + username_reg);\n                    if (!rs.next()) {\n                        System.out.println(\"No rows matched; input treated as data.\");\n                    } else {\n                        do {\n                            System.out.println(\"Matched userid: \" + rs.getString(\"userid\"));\n                        } while (rs.next());\n                    }\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    private static void setup(Connection con) throws SQLException {\n        try (Statement st = con.createStatement()) {\n            st.execute(\"create table sql_challenge_users (userid varchar(100) primary key)\");\n            st.execute(\"insert into sql_challenge_users(userid) values ('tom'), ('alice')\");\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Why this prevents injection\n`PreparedStatement` sends SQL and user input separately.  \nSo this unsafe code:\n```java\n\"select userid from sql_challenge_users where userid = '\" + username_reg + \"'\"\n```\nbecomes:\n```java\nPreparedStatement ps =\n    con.prepareStatement(\"select userid from sql_challenge_users where userid = ?\");\nps.setString(1, username_reg);\n```\n\n### Alternative JDBC drivers\n- PostgreSQL:\n```xml\n<dependency>\n  <groupId>org.postgresql</groupId>\n  <artifactId>postgresql</artifactId>\n  <version>42.7.3</version>\n</dependency>\n```\n- MySQL:\n```xml\n<dependency>\n  <groupId>com.mysql</groupId>\n  <artifactId>mysql-connector-j</artifactId>\n  <version>8.4.0</version>\n</dependency>\n```\n- MariaDB:\n```xml\n<dependency>\n  <groupId>org.mariadb.jdbc</groupId>\n  <artifactId>mariadb-java-client</artifactId>\n  <version>3.4.1</version>\n</dependency>\n```\n- SQLite:\n```xml\n<dependency>\n  <groupId>org.xerial</groupId>\n  <artifactId>sqlite-jdbc</artifactId>\n  <version>3.46.0.0</version>\n</dependency>\n```\n\n___\n\n\n**References (SQL injection)**\n\n- [CAPEC-66: SQL Injection](https://capec.mitre.org/data/definitions/66.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [OWASP: Top 10 A03_2021-Injection](https://owasp.org/Top10/A03_2021-Injection/)\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet)\n- [OWASP: Query Parameterization Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Query_Parameterization_Cheat_Sheet)\n\n\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
