            {
              "id": "cf2c416b-833e-3cf5-9b7e-81f7825c0016",
              "name": "Promise Without Catch Handler",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unhandled Promise Rejection Vulnerability\" in JavaScript occurs when a Promise is rejected, but this rejection is not caught or handled with `.catch()`. This can lead to unexpected application behavior, including but not limited to crashes, \"hangs\", or incorrect operation. It can also potentially lead to security vulnerabilities if the rejection is due to a failed security check or similar.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always handle promise rejections. This can be done by appending a `.catch()` block to your promise chain. The `.catch()` block will catch any errors that occur in the promise chain. If an error is thrown in a `.then()` block and there is no `.catch()` block, the error will go unhandled.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the provided code:\n\n```javascript\n$.ajax({\n    type: 'POST',\n    url: 'JWT/final/follow/' + user\n}).then(function (result) {\n    $(\"#toast\").append(result);\n}).catch(function (error) {\n    console.error('Error occurred:', error);\n});\n```\n\nIn this code, if the AJAX request fails for any reason, the error will be caught and logged to the console.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- jQuery: For the `$` function, `$.ajax`, and `$(\"#toast\").append(result)`.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unhandled Promise Rejection](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Nodejs_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html#unhandled-promise-rejections)\n- [CWE-754: Improper Check for Unusual or Exceptional Conditions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/754.html)"
              },
