            {
              "id": "d3856443-1080-3d5a-8687-a5101e79037b",
              "name": "Improper Unicode Handling",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unicode Transformations Mismanagement Vulnerability\" in Java refers to the improper handling of Unicode transformations, which can lead to various security issues such as information disclosure, bypassing of security controls, or even execution of arbitrary code. This vulnerability arises when a program does not properly handle Unicode encoding/decoding, or when it incorrectly transforms Unicode data to another character set.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the vulnerability may not be directly related to Unicode transformations, but it's worth noting that the use of `equalsIgnoreCase()` method could potentially lead to security issues. This method is case-insensitive, which means it could allow an attacker to bypass security checks by using different case combinations of the same string.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it's recommended to:\n\n- Always validate and sanitize input data.\n- Use secure methods for comparing strings, such as `MessageDigest.isEqual()` for comparing hashed values.\n- Avoid using case-insensitive methods for security-critical operations.\n- Use proper Unicode handling libraries and methods.\n\n## Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere's a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```java\nimport java.security.MessageDigest;\nimport java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;\nimport java.math.BigInteger;\n\n// ...\n\nMessageDigest md = MessageDigest.getInstance(\"SHA-512\");\nbyte[] hashedBytes = md.digest(getWebSession().getUserName().getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8));\nString hashedString = new BigInteger(1, hashedBytes).toString(16);\n\nif (hashedString.equals(secret)) {\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- A library for handling web sessions, such as Java Servlet API.\n- A library for SHA-512 hashing, such as Java's built-in `java.security.MessageDigest`.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Java Encoding Project](https://owasp.org/www-project-java-encoder/)\n- [OWASP String Validation](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Input_Validation_Cheat_Sheet.html#string-validation)\n\n## CWE\n\nThis vulnerability can be related to:\n\n- [CWE-20: Improper Input Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html)\n- [CWE-707: Improper Neutralization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/707.html)\n- [CWE-759: Use of a One-Way Hash without a Salt](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/759.html)"
              },
