              "id": "d9f89c03-962b-3d11-9afa-32da18093ed5",
              "name": "Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nServer-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) is a vulnerability that allows an attacker to induce the server-side application to make HTTP requests to an arbitrary domain of the attacker's choosing. In a typical SSRF example, the attacker might cause the server to make a connection back to itself, or to other web-based services within the organization's infrastructure, or to external third-party systems.\n\nFile Disclosure via URLConnection is a vulnerability that allows an attacker to read files from the server's file system that they should not have access to. This can happen when an application uses user-supplied input to construct a file path without properly validating or sanitizing the input.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the application is vulnerable to both SSRF and File Disclosure because it uses user-supplied input to create a URL without any validation or sanitization.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate these vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n1. Validate user-supplied input: Ensure that the URL or file path is safe before using it. This could involve checking that the URL is in a list of allowed URLs, or that the file path does not contain any directory traversal characters (`../`).\n\n2. Use allow-lists: Only allow connections to known, trusted domains or file paths.\n\n3. Limit the impact of SSRF: Use a firewall to prevent the server from making arbitrary connections to internal services.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere is a simple fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```java\nString trustedUrl = \"http://example.com\";\nif (url.equals(trustedUrl)) {\n    try (InputStream in = new URL(url).openStream()) {\n        // ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, the application only opens a connection if the URL is a known, trusted URL.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet uses the `java.net.URL` and `java.io.InputStream` classes, which are part of the Java standard library. No additional library dependencies are required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Server-Side Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Server_Side_Request_Forgery)\n- [OWASP Unrestricted File Upload](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Unrestricted_File_Upload)\n- [CWE-918: Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/918.html)\n- [CWE-22: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html)"
              },
