            {
              "id": "ddadc0d6-5d46-3ba6-82c9-5e239e96d2d3",
              "name": "Potential JDBC Injection",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "\nThe input values included in SQL queries need to be passed in safely. Bind variables in prepared statements can be used to easily mitigate the risk of SQL injection. Alternatively to prepare statements, each parameter can be escaped manually.\n\n**Solution (Prepared Statements):**\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM User WHERE id = ?\";\nPreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npreparedStatement.setString(1, inputId);\nResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery();\n```\n\n**Solution (Encoding):**\n\n```java\nimport org.owasp.esapi.Encoder;\ncreateQuery(\"select * from User where id = '\" + Encoder.encodeForSQL(inputId) + \"'\");\n```\n\n## In Context Remediation\n```\nVulnerable Query: \"select password from challenge_users where userid = '\" + username_login + \"' and password = '\" + password_login + \"'\"\nRemediated Query: ## Description\n\nThis code builds a SQL query by concatenating untrusted request parameters directly into the statement text. In Java, this allows an attacker to change the meaning of the query by supplying crafted values for the username or password fields.\n\nUse a PreparedStatement with bind parameters instead of string concatenation. Parameterized queries keep user input as data, prevent SQL syntax injection, and are the standard JDBC defense for authentication queries and all other database access paths.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nReplace every SQL statement assembled with + concatenation, StringBuilder, or String.format using request data with PreparedStatement placeholders. Apply the same pattern consistently for SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, and stored procedure calls.\n\nDo not rely on input filtering or escaping as the primary defense. Validate inputs for expected format and length, but always bind values through JDBC parameters. Also avoid exposing raw database errors to users and use least-privileged database accounts for the application.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~java\nString sql = \"SELECT password FROM challenge_users WHERE userid = ? AND password = ?\";\n\ntry (Connection connection = dataSource.getConnection();\n     PreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n    preparedStatement.setString(1, username_login);\n    preparedStatement.setString(2, password_login);\n\n    try (ResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery()) {\n        if (resultSet.next()) {\n            String password = resultSet.getString(\"password\");\n            // handle successful authentication result\n        } else {\n            // handle failed authentication result\n        }\n    }\n}\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~java\nimport java.sql.Connection;\nimport java.sql.PreparedStatement;\nimport java.sql.ResultSet;\nimport javax.sql.DataSource;\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Oracle JDBC Basics: Using Prepared Statements](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/jdbc/basics/prepared.html)\n\n```\n#### Remediation 1\nBelow is a minimal **Java console** example that shows the unsafe query and the safe **prepared statement** version.\n\n### `pom.xml` dependencies\n```xml\n<dependencies>\n    <!-- In-memory DB for reproducible demo -->\n    <dependency>\n        <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n        <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n        <version>2.2.224</version>\n    </dependency>\n</dependencies>\n```\n\n### `Main.java`\n```java\nimport java.sql.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        String url = \"jdbc:h2:mem:test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1\";\n\n        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url)) {\n            try (Statement st = con.createStatement()) {\n                st.execute(\"CREATE TABLE challenge_users (userid VARCHAR(50), password VARCHAR(50))\");\n                st.execute(\"INSERT INTO challenge_users VALUES ('alice', 'secret')\");\n            }\n\n            String username_login = \"alice' --\";\n            String password_login = \"wrong\";\n\n            System.out.println(\"Unsafe login: \" + unsafeLogin(con, username_login, password_login));\n            System.out.println(\"Safe login:   \" + safeLogin(con, username_login, password_login));\n        }\n    }\n\n    static boolean unsafeLogin(Connection con, String username_login, String password_login) throws SQLException {\n        String sql = \"select password from challenge_users where userid = '\"\n                + username_login + \"' and password = '\" + password_login + \"'\";\n        System.out.println(\"Unsafe SQL: \" + sql);\n\n        try (Statement st = con.createStatement();\n             ResultSet rs = st.executeQuery(sql)) {\n            return rs.next();\n        }\n    }\n\n    static boolean safeLogin(Connection con, String username_login, String password_login) throws SQLException {\n        String sql = \"select password from challenge_users where userid = ? and password = ?\";\n        try (PreparedStatement ps = con.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n            ps.setString(1, username_login);\n            ps.setString(2, password_login);\n\n            try (ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) {\n                return rs.next();\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Why this prevents SQL injection\n`PreparedStatement` sends SQL and data separately. Input like `alice' --` is treated as a literal string, not executable SQL.\n\n### Run\n```bash\nmvn compile exec:java -Dexec.mainClass=Main\n```\n\n### Alternative JDBC drivers\n- PostgreSQL: `org.postgresql:postgresql`\n- MySQL: `com.mysql:mysql-connector-j`\n- MariaDB: `org.mariadb.jdbc:mariadb-java-client`\n- SQLite: `org.xerial:sqlite-jdbc`\n- Microsoft SQL Server: `com.microsoft.sqlserver:mssql-jdbc`\n- Oracle: `com.oracle.database.jdbc:ojdbc11`\n\n#### Remediation 2\nBelow is a minimal **Java console** example showing the **safe** version using a **PreparedStatement**.\n\n### `pom.xml` dependencies\n```xml\n<dependencies>\n    <!-- SQLite JDBC driver -->\n    <dependency>\n        <groupId>org.xerial</groupId>\n        <artifactId>sqlite-jdbc</artifactId>\n        <version>3.46.1.3</version>\n    </dependency>\n</dependencies>\n```\n\n### `Main.java`\n```java\nimport java.sql.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        String url = \"jdbc:sqlite::memory:\";\n\n        try (Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url)) {\n            setup(conn);\n\n            String usernameLogin = \"alice' OR '1'='1\";\n            String passwordLogin = \"anything\";\n\n            boolean ok = safeLogin(conn, usernameLogin, passwordLogin);\n            System.out.println(\"Login success: \" + ok); // false\n        }\n    }\n\n    static void setup(Connection conn) throws SQLException {\n        try (Statement st = conn.createStatement()) {\n            st.executeUpdate(\n                \"CREATE TABLE challenge_users (\" +\n                \"userid TEXT PRIMARY KEY, password TEXT NOT NULL)\"\n            );\n        }\n\n        try (PreparedStatement ps =\n                 conn.prepareStatement(\n                     \"INSERT INTO challenge_users(userid, password) VALUES (?, ?)\"\n                 )) {\n            ps.setString(1, \"alice\");\n            ps.setString(2, \"secret123\");\n            ps.executeUpdate();\n        }\n    }\n\n    static boolean safeLogin(Connection conn, String usernameLogin, String passwordLogin)\n            throws SQLException {\n        String sql =\n            \"SELECT password FROM challenge_users \" +\n            \"WHERE userid = ? AND password = ?\";\n\n        try (PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n            ps.setString(1, usernameLogin);\n            ps.setString(2, passwordLogin);\n\n            try (ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()) {\n                return rs.next();\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Why this prevents SQL injection\nThe vulnerable pattern concatenates input into SQL:\n```java\n\"select password from challenge_users where userid = '\" + username_login +\n\"' and password = '\" + password_login + \"'\"\n```\nWith `PreparedStatement`, user input is bound as **data**, not executable SQL, so payloads like `alice' OR '1'='1` do not alter query logic.\n\n### Alternative JDBC drivers\n```xml\n<!-- PostgreSQL -->\n<dependency>\n    <groupId>org.postgresql</groupId>\n    <artifactId>postgresql</artifactId>\n    <version>42.7.7</version>\n</dependency>\n\n<!-- MySQL -->\n<dependency>\n    <groupId>com.mysql</groupId>\n    <artifactId>mysql-connector-j</artifactId>\n    <version>9.3.0</version>\n</dependency>\n\n<!-- H2 -->\n<dependency>\n    <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    <version>2.3.232</version>\n</dependency>\n```\n\n___\n\n\n**References (SQL injection)**\n\n- [CAPEC-66: SQL Injection](https://capec.mitre.org/data/definitions/66.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [OWASP: Top 10 A03_2021-Injection](https://owasp.org/Top10/A03_2021-Injection/)\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet)\n- [OWASP: Query Parameterization Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Query_Parameterization_Cheat_Sheet)\n\n\n"
              },
