            {
              "id": "e0cfa1bf-809b-3751-8ae3-e2077bfaeffb",
              "name": "Obfuscated Object Names Violate Naming Standards",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Non-Standard and Improperly Named Objects Vulnerability\" in JavaScript refers to the practice of using non-standard or obfuscated object names in the code. This can lead to confusion, difficulty in code maintenance, and potential security vulnerabilities. In the provided code, hexadecimal escape sequences are used to represent string literals, which is a form of obfuscation. This can make it harder for developers to understand the code, and easier for attackers to hide malicious code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, developers should adhere to standard naming conventions and avoid obfuscation. Code should be written to be as clear and understandable as possible. This not only helps to prevent potential security vulnerabilities, but also makes the code easier to maintain and debug.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code can be fixed by replacing the hexadecimal escape sequences with their string literal equivalents. Here's the fixed code:\n\n```javascript\nvar names = [\"CaptainJack\", \"BlackPearl\"];\nxhttp.send(JSON.stringify({username: names[0], password: names[1]}));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any library dependencies. However, it assumes the existence of an `xhttp` object, which is typically created using the `XMLHttpRequest` API or the `fetch` API.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Code Review Guide](https://owasp.org/www-project-code-review-guide/)\n- [CWE-247: Reliance on DNS Lookups in a Security Decision](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/247.html)\n\nPlease note that the CWE link does not directly correspond to the described vulnerability, as there is no specific CWE for non-standard or improperly named objects. However, it does relate to the broader issue of code obfuscation."
              },
              "properties": {
