              "id": "e0ea0aba-5f5f-3345-a106-4a595d05b3db",
              "name": "User Controlled Data In HTML String May Result In XSS",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA potential Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is used in an HTML string. In the provided JavaScript code, the `result` variable is concatenated to a string that is then used to set the `src` attribute of an HTML element. If an attacker can control the value of `result`, they could inject malicious scripts that would be executed when the HTML is rendered in a user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always sanitize user-controlled data before using it in an HTML context. This can be done by using a library that provides HTML encoding functions, or by using built-in JavaScript functions like `encodeURIComponent()`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere's how you could fix the provided code:\n\n```javascript\ndocument.getElementById(\"previewRetrieval\").src = \"data:image/png;base64,\" + encodeURIComponent(result);\n```\n\nIn this version of the code, `encodeURIComponent()` is used to encode the `result` variable. This function will encode special characters that could be used to inject malicious scripts.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any library dependencies. It uses only built-in JavaScript functions and properties.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e2b93688-b4ae-3bcc-bd38-3eb9cccae361",
              "name": "File Disclosure",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Disclosure Vulnerability in Spring File\" is a type of security vulnerability that occurs when an application built with the Spring Framework in Java unintentionally exposes sensitive information to users. This can happen when the application uses user input to construct file paths without properly validating or sanitizing the input. An attacker can exploit this vulnerability to access, read, or even modify files that they are not supposed to have access to.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using user input to construct file paths directly. If it is necessary to use user input in file paths, the input should be properly validated and sanitized to ensure that it does not contain any malicious values. Additionally, the application should be configured to limit the access permissions of users to prevent them from accessing sensitive files.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to fix this vulnerability in a Spring MVC application:\n\n```java\nimport org.springframework.web.servlet.ModelAndView;\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.PathVariable;\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMethod;\n\n@RequestMapping(value = \"/download/{fileName}\", method = RequestMethod.GET)\npublic ModelAndView downloadFile(@PathVariable(\"fileName\") String fileName) {\n    // Validate the file name to ensure it does not contain any malicious values\n    if (!fileName.matches(\"[a-zA-Z0-9\\\\.]+\")) {\n        throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"Invalid file name\");\n    }\n\n    // Construct the file path\n    String filePath = \"/downloads/\" + fileName;\n\n    // Create the ModelAndView object\n    ModelAndView modelAndView = new ModelAndView();\n    modelAndView.setViewName(filePath);\n\n    return modelAndView;\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Spring Web MVC\n- Spring Core\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cheat Sheet: File Upload](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/File_Upload_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-22: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html)\n- [CWE-200: Information Exposure](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-22",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
