              "id": "e4d4faf3-afd3-3929-968e-228a3dcaac86",
              "name": "SQL Injection Protection Relies On Keyword Stripping",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to SQL Injection attacks. The vulnerability arises from the fact that the code is trying to prevent SQL Injection by stripping out certain SQL keywords and blocking spaces. This is a weak form of input validation and can be easily bypassed by an attacker.\n\nThe code converts the user input to uppercase and then removes the SQL keywords \"FROM\" and \"SELECT\". However, this approach is flawed because SQL is not case sensitive and an attacker can use lower case or mixed case SQL keywords to bypass this check. Also, the code checks if the user input contains a space and if it does, it rejects the input. This can also be bypassed by an attacker by using comments or other SQL syntax that does not require spaces.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best way to prevent SQL Injection attacks is to use parameterized queries or prepared statements. This ensures that user input is always treated as literal data and not executable code. Also, it is recommended to use a web application firewall (WAF) that can detect and block SQL Injection attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code using parameterized queries:\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE userId = ?\";\nPreparedStatement stmt = connection.prepareStatement(query);\nstmt.setString(1, userId);\nResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery();\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Java SQL library (java.sql.*)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
