            {
              "id": "f26b8a22-e5c6-3c67-a1d6-37ee08651ded",
              "name": "Predictable Secret Derived From Username or Email",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nWeak password recovery token validation. This code accepts a reset value derived directly from the current username by reversing it and comparing it with user input. Because the value is deterministic and based on predictable account data, an attacker who knows or can guess the username can derive the same token without access to the user’s email or any server-side secret.\n\nIn Java, password reset and account recovery flows must validate a cryptographically random, single-use, time-limited token generated on the server and stored server-side with an expiration timestamp. For the sink shown here, replace the comparison against StringUtils.reverse(getWebSession().getUserName()) with lookup and verification of a random token associated with the authenticated recovery request, then invalidate it immediately after successful use.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not derive recovery secrets from usernames, email addresses, local-parts, timestamps, reversible transforms, or any other predictable user attribute. Generate reset tokens with java.security.SecureRandom, make them sufficiently long, bind them to the intended account, store them server-side, expire them quickly, and invalidate them after one successful use. Deliver the token over a separate channel such as email, and rate-limit reset attempts to reduce brute-force and enumeration risk.\n\nKeep reset logic separate from the active web session identity where possible, because a session username is not proof that a recovery token is legitimate. After successful validation, clear the token, record the reset event, and require the user to choose a new password through the normal password hashing flow. Also return uniform error messages for invalid and expired tokens so the endpoint does not leak account state.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~java\nimport java.security.SecureRandom;\nimport java.time.Instant;\nimport java.util.Base64;\nimport java.util.Objects;\n\nprivate static final SecureRandom SECURE_RANDOM = new SecureRandom();\nprivate static final long RESET_TOKEN_TTL_SECONDS = 900;\n\npublic String createPasswordResetToken(User user) {\n    byte[] bytes = new byte[32];\n    SECURE_RANDOM.nextBytes(bytes);\n    String token = Base64.getUrlEncoder().withoutPadding().encodeToString(bytes);\n\n    user.setPasswordResetToken(token);\n    user.setPasswordResetTokenExpiresAt(Instant.now().plusSeconds(RESET_TOKEN_TTL_SECONDS));\n    userRepository.save(user);\n\n    return token;\n}\n\npublic boolean isValidPasswordResetToken(User user, String suppliedToken) {\n    if (suppliedToken == null) {\n        return false;\n    }\n\n    String storedToken = user.getPasswordResetToken();\n    Instant expiresAt = user.getPasswordResetTokenExpiresAt();\n\n    if (storedToken == null || expiresAt == null) {\n        return false;\n    }\n\n    if (Instant.now().isAfter(expiresAt)) {\n        return false;\n    }\n\n    return Objects.equals(storedToken, suppliedToken);\n}\n\npublic void handlePasswordReset(User user, String suppliedToken, String newPassword) {\n    if (!isValidPasswordResetToken(user, suppliedToken)) {\n        throw new SecurityException(\"Invalid or expired password reset token\");\n    }\n\n    user.setPasswordHash(passwordEncoder.encode(newPassword));\n    user.setPasswordResetToken(null);\n    user.setPasswordResetTokenExpiresAt(null);\n    userRepository.save(user);\n}\n\nif (!isValidPasswordResetToken(getWebSession().getUser(), uniqueCode)) {\n    throw new SecurityException(\"Invalid or expired password reset token\");\n}\n\ngetWebSession().getUser().setPasswordResetToken(null);\ngetWebSession().getUser().setPasswordResetTokenExpiresAt(null);\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~java\nimport java.security.SecureRandom;\nimport java.time.Instant;\nimport java.util.Base64;\nimport java.util.Objects;\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [OWASP Forgot Password Cheat Sheet](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Forgot_Password_Cheat_Sheet)\n- [CWE-640: Weak Password Recovery Mechanism for Forgotten Password](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/640.html)\n- [OWASP Forgot Password Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Forgot_Password_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [Java SecureRandom API](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/security/SecureRandom.html)\n- [Java Instant API](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/time/Instant.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-640",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/640.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-640"
                ]
              }
