            {
              "id": "f299b61c-09c8-30b9-b815-73505aed7271",
              "name": "User Controlled Data Can Lead To XSS Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern is a common security vulnerability in JavaScript programming. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. This allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the vulnerability arises from the use of the `append()` function which directly inserts user-controlled data (`comment`) into the HTML DOM (`field`). If the `comment` data is not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape untrusted HTTP request data based on the context in the HTML output (HTML body, HTML attribute, JavaScript, CSS, or URL) that the data lands. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nYou should use a safe method to insert user-controlled data into the HTML DOM. For instance, you can use the `text()` function which escapes the content and prevents the execution of any script:\n\n```javascript\n$(field).text(comment);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the jQuery library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f2b32de9-e394-3895-95d6-506795b8b343",
              "name": "Controller Accepts Hardcoded Credentials",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability in Authentication Logic is a common security issue in Java programming. It occurs when developers embed sensitive information such as usernames, passwords, or keys directly into their source code. This practice is insecure because it exposes sensitive data to anyone who has access to the code. In the provided code snippet, the username \"CaptainJack\" and the password \"BlackPearl\" are hardcoded, which is a security risk.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information in your source code. Instead, use secure methods of storing and retrieving these values, such as environment variables or secure configuration files. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the values, you can retrieve them from environment variables:\n\n```java\nString username = System.getenv(\"USERNAME\");\nString password = System.getenv(\"PASSWORD\");\n\nif (username.equals(username) && password.equals(password)) {\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `USERNAME` and `PASSWORD` environment variables should be set in the environment where the application is running. This way, the sensitive data is not exposed in the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A2: Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authentication_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
