              "id": "fb775aac-9188-3f22-a741-eec7b9d8aef3",
              "name": "User Controlled Data In HTML String May Result In XSS",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. This is because it directly uses user-controlled data (`data.name`, `data.color`, `data.size`) in an HTML string that is then inserted into the page using jQuery's `.html()` method. If an attacker can control the `data` object, they could inject malicious scripts into the page, which would then be executed in the context of the user's session.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled data before inserting it into an HTML context. This can be done using JavaScript's built-in methods for encoding special characters, or by using a library that provides this functionality.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code snippet that uses jQuery's `.text()` method to safely insert user-controlled data into the page:\n\n```javascript\nwebgoat.customjs.jquery('#idor-profile').html(\n    'name:' + $('<div/>').text(data.name).html() + '<br/>'+\n    'color:' + $('<div/>').text(data.color).html() + '<br/>'+\n    'size:' + $('<div/>').text(data.size).html() + '<br/>'\n);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- jQuery\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
